  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator wants to display all currently active swap areas including their type, size, and usage on a running system. Which command provides this information?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A junior administrator accidentally changed the permissions on /etc/passwd to 777. A senior administrator needs to restore the correct permissions. What are the correct permissions for /etc/passwd and which command sets them?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"chmod 600 /etc/passwd — owner read/write only"},{"id":"b","text":"chmod 644 /etc/passwd — owner read/write, group and others read-only"},{"id":"c","text":"chmod 640 /etc/passwd — owner read/write, group read, others no access"},{"id":"d","text":"chmod 755 /etc/passwd — owner read/write/execute, group and others read/execute"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$/etc/passwd must be world-readable because many programs and utilities (such as 'ls -l' for username resolution, 'id', and others) need to read it to map UIDs to usernames. The correct permissions are 644 (rw-r--r--), giving the root owner read and write access, while the group and all other users have read-only access. 600 would block non-root users and processes from reading the file, breaking many system functions. 640 would still break world-readable requirements. 755 would add execute bits which are inappropriate and potentially dangerous for a text file.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/passwd.5.html","label":"Linux man page — passwd(5)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ Study Guide — File Permissions"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A junior administrator accidentally changed the permissions on /etc/passwd to 777. A senior administrator needs to restore the correct permissions. What are the correct permissions for /etc/passwd and which command sets them?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to extend an existing LVM logical volume named 'lv_data' in the volume group 'vg_storage' by 10 GB and immediately resize the ext4 filesystem on it — all in a single command. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"lvextend -L +10G /dev/vg_storage/lv_data && resize2fs /dev/vg_storage/lv_data"},{"id":"b","text":"lvextend -r -L +10G /dev/vg_storage/lv_data"},{"id":"c","text":"lvresize -L +10G /dev/vg_storage/lv_data"},{"id":"d","text":"vgextend vg_storage /dev/sdb && lvextend -l +100%FREE /dev/vg_storage/lv_data"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'lvextend -r -L +10G /dev/vg_storage/lv_data' uses the -r (--resizefs) flag, which calls the appropriate filesystem resize tool (resize2fs for ext4, xfs_growfs for XFS) automatically after extending the logical volume — accomplishing the task in a single command. Option A is functionally correct but uses two separate commands chained with &&, not a single command. Option C uses lvresize without -r, so the filesystem is not resized and the new space remains unusable. Option D adds a physical volume to the volume group first and then extends to 100% free space, which is a different operation and does not target a specific +10G extension.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_logical_volumes/modifying-the-size-of-a-logical-volume_configuring-and-managing-logical-volumes","label":"Red Hat — Extending a logical volume and its filesystem"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lvextend.8.html","label":"Linux man page — lvextend(8)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to extend an existing LVM logical volume named 'lv_data' in the volume group 'vg_storage' by 10 GB and immediately resize the ext4 filesystem on it — all in a single command. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator writes a Bash script that must exit immediately if any command within the script returns a non-zero exit code. Which set command option should be placed at the top of the script to enforce this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"set -u"},{"id":"b","text":"set -x"},{"id":"c","text":"set -e"},{"id":"d","text":"set -n"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$set -e (errexit) causes a Bash script to exit immediately when any command exits with a non-zero status, preventing subsequent commands from running after an error. set -u causes the script to treat unset variables as errors. set -x enables debug trace output, printing each command before execution. set -n reads commands but does not execute them, which is used for syntax checking.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/html_node/The-Set-Builtin.html","label":"GNU Bash Manual – The Set Builtin"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator writes a Bash script that must exit immediately if any command within the script returns a non-zero exit code. Which set command option should be placed at the top of the script to enforce this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer wants to run a containerized NGINX web server using Podman so that it is accessible on port 8080 of the host machine, maps to port 80 inside the container, and runs in the background. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"podman run -p 80:8080 -d nginx"},{"id":"b","text":"podman run -p 8080:80 -d nginx"},{"id":"c","text":"podman run -p 8080:80 nginx"},{"id":"d","text":"podman run --expose 8080 -d nginx"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The -p flag syntax is HOST_PORT:CONTAINER_PORT, so -p 8080:80 binds host port 8080 to container port 80. The -d flag runs the container in detached (background) mode. Option A reverses the port mapping, binding host port 80 to container port 8080. Option C omits -d so the container runs in the foreground. Option D uses --expose, which only documents a port for inter-container communication and does not publish it to the host.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.podman.io/en/latest/markdown/podman-run.1.html","label":"Podman Documentation – podman run"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer wants to run a containerized NGINX web server using Podman so that it is accessible on port 8080 of the host machine, maps to port 80 inside the container, and runs in the background. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to automate a recurring task that executes a custom script /opt/scripts/backup.sh every weekday (Monday through Friday) at 2:30 AM. Which crontab entry is correct?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"30 2 * * 1-5 /opt/scripts/backup.sh"},{"id":"b","text":"2 30 * * 1-5 /opt/scripts/backup.sh"},{"id":"c","text":"30 2 1-5 * * /opt/scripts/backup.sh"},{"id":"d","text":"30 2 * * MON-FRI /opt/scripts/backup.sh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The crontab field order is: minute, hour, day-of-month, month, day-of-week. For 2:30 AM weekdays, the correct entry is '30 2 * * 1-5'. Option B swaps minute and hour fields, which would run at 30:02 — an invalid time. Option C incorrectly places the day-of-week range (1-5) in the day-of-month field. Option D uses the three-letter abbreviation MON-FRI, which is valid in many cron implementations; however, option A using numeric 1-5 is universally portable and is the more precise standard form tested on the exam.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/automating_system_tasks/index","label":"Red Hat – Automating system tasks with cron"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to automate a recurring task that executes a custom script /opt/scripts/backup.sh every weekday (Monday through Friday) at 2:30 AM. Which crontab entry is correct?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems engineer is writing a Bash script that accepts a filename as its first positional parameter. The script must verify that the file exists and is readable before processing it. Which conditional expression correctly performs this check?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"if [ -e \"$1\" ]; then"},{"id":"b","text":"if [ -r \"$1\" ]; then"},{"id":"c","text":"if [ -w \"$1\" ]; then"},{"id":"d","text":"if [ -x \"$1\" ]; then"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The -r test operator checks that the specified file exists AND that the current user has read permission on it, which satisfies both requirements simultaneously. -e only tests for existence without checking permissions, so a file could exist but be unreadable. -w tests for write permission, which is unrelated to reading the file. -x tests for execute permission, also unrelated to readability.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/html_node/Bash-Conditional-Expressions.html","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Bash Conditional Expressions"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems engineer is writing a Bash script that accepts a filename as its first positional parameter. The script must verify that the file exists and is readable before processing it. Which conditional expression correctly performs this check?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team uses Ansible to manage a fleet of Linux servers. A playbook task must install the 'httpd' package only on hosts that belong to the 'webservers' inventory group. The playbook currently targets all hosts. Which Ansible mechanism should be used within the task definition to restrict its execution to the 'webservers' group?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a 'hosts: webservers' line directly inside the task block"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the 'when: inventory_hostname in groups[\"webservers\"]' conditional on the task"},{"id":"c","text":"Use the 'delegate_to: webservers' directive on the task"},{"id":"d","text":"Add a 'limit: webservers' parameter to the task's module arguments"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Ansible's 'when' directive allows conditional execution of tasks. The expression 'inventory_hostname in groups["webservers"]' evaluates to true only for hosts that are members of the webservers group, restricting execution accordingly. 'hosts:' is a play-level keyword and cannot be placed inside an individual task block. 'delegate_to' redirects task execution to a different host entirely, it does not filter which hosts run the task. There is no 'limit' parameter within a task's module arguments; --limit is a command-line flag for ansible-playbook, not a task-level directive.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/playbook_guide/playbooks_conditionals.html","label":"Ansible Documentation – Conditionals"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team uses Ansible to manage a fleet of Linux servers. A playbook task must install the 'httpd' package only on hosts that belong to the 'webservers' inventory group. The playbook currently targets all hosts. Which Ansible mechanism should be used within the task definition to restrict its execution to the 'webservers' group?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a server is responding very slowly. Running `top` reveals that a single process named `data_sync` is consuming 98% CPU. The administrator wants to reduce its CPU priority without killing the process. Which command should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"kill -9 $(pgrep data_sync)"},{"id":"b","text":"renice +15 -p $(pgrep data_sync)"},{"id":"c","text":"nice -n -15 data_sync"},{"id":"d","text":"ionice -c 1 -p $(pgrep data_sync)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The `renice` command changes the scheduling priority of an already-running process. Using `renice +15` assigns a higher niceness value (lower CPU priority), which reduces the process's competition for CPU time. Option A kills the process outright. Option C uses `nice` which only sets priority at launch time, not for an existing process. Option D uses `ionice` which adjusts I/O scheduling priority, not CPU priority.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/renice.1.html","label":"Linux man page: renice"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a server is responding very slowly. Running `top` reveals that a single process named `data_sync` is consuming 98% CPU. The administrator wants to reduce its CPU priority without killing the process. Which command should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator receives reports that users cannot log in via SSH. The SSH daemon appears to be running, but connections are immediately refused. Reviewing `/var/log/auth.log` shows: `error: Could not load host key: /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key`. What is the most likely fix?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Restart the network interface with `ip link set eth0 down && ip link set eth0 up`"},{"id":"b","text":"Regenerate the SSH host keys using `ssh-keygen -A`"},{"id":"c","text":"Edit `/etc/ssh/sshd_config` and set `PermitRootLogin yes`"},{"id":"d","text":"Flush the firewall rules with `iptables -F`"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The error message indicates that the SSH host key file is missing or unreadable. The command `ssh-keygen -A` regenerates all missing host keys for the system, which resolves this error. Option A addresses network issues, which is unrelated to the missing key error. Option C changes root login behavior but does not fix missing host keys. Option D clears firewall rules, which is also unrelated to the described error.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man.openbsd.org/ssh-keygen","label":"OpenSSH ssh-keygen documentation"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator receives reports that users cannot log in via SSH. The SSH daemon appears to be running, but connections are immediately refused. Reviewing `/var/log/auth.log` shows: `error: Could not load host key: /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key`. What is the most likely fix?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A junior administrator reports that a critical script at `/opt/scripts/backup.sh` fails with `Permission denied` when run by the `backupsvc` service account. The file permissions show `-rw-r--r--`. What is the minimum change needed to allow `backupsvc` to execute the script without granting unnecessary access to other users?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"chmod 777 /opt/scripts/backup.sh"},{"id":"b","text":"chmod o+x /opt/scripts/backup.sh"},{"id":"c","text":"chown backupsvc /opt/scripts/backup.sh && chmod u+x /opt/scripts/backup.sh"},{"id":"d","text":"chmod 644 /opt/scripts/backup.sh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The correct approach is to assign ownership of the file to `backupsvc` with `chown` and then add execute permission for the owner with `chmod u+x`. This grants execute access exclusively to the `backupsvc` account without broadening permissions to group or others. Option A grants rwx to everyone, which is a security risk. Option B adds execute for 'others', which is broader than needed. Option D sets 644, which does not add any execute bit at all.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chmod.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chmod"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chown.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chown"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A junior administrator reports that a critical script at `/opt/scripts/backup.sh` fails with `Permission denied` when run by the `backupsvc` service account. The file permissions show `-rw-r--r--`. What is the minimum change needed to allow `backupsvc` to execute the script without granting unnecessary access to other users?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server is running out of disk space on `/var`. Running `df -h` confirms the filesystem is 100% full, but `du -sh /var/*` shows only 60% utilization. What is the most likely cause of this discrepancy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The filesystem has too many inodes allocated for small files"},{"id":"b","text":"One or more deleted files are still held open by running processes, consuming space not reflected by `du`"},{"id":"c","text":"The partition has a misaligned block size causing excess overhead"},{"id":"d","text":"The `/var` mount point has been remounted read-only"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a file is deleted but a process still holds an open file descriptor to it, the operating system does not release the disk blocks until the process closes the file. `du` only shows space used by files visible in the directory tree, while `df` reports actual block usage including those held by open descriptors. To identify these files, `lsof | grep '(deleted)'` can be used. Option A relates to inode exhaustion, which would appear differently. Option C is unrelated to a discrepancy between `df` and `du`. Option D would cause write errors, not a space discrepancy.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lsof.8.html","label":"Linux man page: lsof"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/2316","label":"Red Hat: Why does df and du report different disk usage?"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server is running out of disk space on `/var`. Running `df -h` confirms the filesystem is 100% full, but `du -sh /var/*` shows only 60% utilization. What is the most likely cause of this discrepancy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a kernel update, a Linux server fails to boot and drops into emergency mode. Which of the following is the BEST first step to diagnose the boot failure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Run `fsck` on all filesystems immediately"},{"id":"b","text":"Boot from the previous kernel entry in the GRUB menu and review `journalctl -xb`"},{"id":"c","text":"Reinstall the operating system from installation media"},{"id":"d","text":"Edit `/etc/fstab` and remove all mount entries"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Booting from the previous working kernel via the GRUB menu is the safest first diagnostic step after a failed kernel update. Once booted successfully, `journalctl -xb` displays the journal for the current boot session, allowing the administrator to identify the root cause of the failure. Option A may cause data corruption if filesystems are mounted. Option C is destructive and premature. Option D would cause more boot failures by removing necessary mounts.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/grub/manual/grub/grub.html","label":"GNU GRUB Manual"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/journalctl.1.html","label":"systemd journalctl man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a kernel update, a Linux server fails to boot and drops into emergency mode. Which of the following is the BEST first step to diagnose the boot failure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user reports they cannot reach an external website by hostname, but `ping 8.8.8.8` succeeds. Which command would BEST help identify whether the issue is DNS-related?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"traceroute 8.8.8.8"},{"id":"b","text":"dig www.example.com"},{"id":"c","text":"netstat -tulpn"},{"id":"d","text":"ip route show"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`dig` is a DNS lookup utility that queries DNS servers directly and returns detailed resolution information. Since ICMP to an IP address works but hostname resolution fails, the issue is almost certainly DNS. `dig` can reveal whether the configured DNS server is reachable and returning correct responses. Option A tests routing paths to an IP, not DNS. Option C shows listening ports. Option D shows the routing table, which is not relevant to hostname resolution failures.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/dig.1.html","label":"Linux man page: dig"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user reports they cannot reach an external website by hostname, but `ping 8.8.8.8` succeeds. Which command would BEST help identify whether the issue is DNS-related?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator runs `systemctl start myapp.service` and receives the error `Failed to start myapp.service: Unit not found`. The service file exists at `/etc/systemd/system/myapp.service`. What is the most likely cause and fix?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The service file has incorrect syntax; validate it with `service myapp validate`"},{"id":"b","text":"systemd has not been made aware of the new unit file; run `systemctl daemon-reload` and retry"},{"id":"c","text":"The service must be enabled before it can be started; run `systemctl enable myapp.service`"},{"id":"d","text":"The `/etc/systemd/system/` directory requires world-readable permissions; run `chmod 777 /etc/systemd/system/`"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a new unit file is added or an existing one is modified, systemd must reload its configuration to recognize the changes. Running `systemctl daemon-reload` instructs systemd to re-scan its unit file directories. Without this step, systemd is unaware of the new file and reports 'Unit not found'. Option A uses an invalid command. Option C enables a service for automatic start at boot but is not required to start it manually. Option D is a serious security risk and is not required.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/systemctl.1.html","label":"systemd systemctl man page"},{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.unit.html","label":"freedesktop.org: systemd unit files"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator runs `systemctl start myapp.service` and receives the error `Failed to start myapp.service: Unit not found`. The service file exists at `/etc/systemd/system/myapp.service`. What is the most likely cause and fix?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server running a web application begins logging `Too many open files` errors. The administrator confirms with `ulimit -n` that the current limit is 1024. The change must survive a reboot. Which file should be edited to permanently increase this limit for the `www-data` user?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/sysctl.conf"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/profile"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/security/limits.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"/proc/sys/fs/file-max"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`/etc/security/limits.conf` is the PAM-based configuration file for setting per-user and per-group resource limits, including `nofile` (number of open files). Adding a line such as `www-data hard nofile 65536` makes the limit persistent across reboots. Option A (`sysctl.conf`) configures kernel parameters globally, not per-user. Option B (`/etc/profile`) sets environment variables for login shells, not hard resource limits. Option D (`/proc/sys/fs/file-max`) is a runtime kernel parameter that resets on reboot.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/limits.conf.5.html","label":"Linux man page: limits.conf"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server running a web application begins logging `Too many open files` errors. The administrator confirms with `ulimit -n` that the current limit is 1024. The change must survive a reboot. Which file should be edited to permanently increase this limit for the `www-data` user?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator attempts to unmount `/mnt/data` and receives the error `umount: /mnt/data: target is busy`. Which command will identify which process is keeping the filesystem busy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"df -h /mnt/data"},{"id":"b","text":"fuser -mv /mnt/data"},{"id":"c","text":"mount | grep /mnt/data"},{"id":"d","text":"blkid /mnt/data"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`fuser -mv /mnt/data` lists all processes that have files open on the specified filesystem, along with the type of access (e.g., open file, current directory, executable). This allows the administrator to identify and terminate the blocking processes before retrying the unmount. Option A shows disk usage but not which process is using the mount. Option C shows mount details but not blocking processes. Option D identifies block device attributes, not process usage.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/fuser.1.html","label":"Linux man page: fuser"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator attempts to unmount `/mnt/data` and receives the error `umount: /mnt/data: target is busy`. Which command will identify which process is keeping the filesystem busy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network-connected Linux server is experiencing intermittent packet loss. The administrator suspects a NIC hardware or driver issue. Which command provides per-interface statistics including error counters such as dropped packets, overruns, and frame errors?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ping -c 100 gateway_ip"},{"id":"b","text":"ip -s link show eth0"},{"id":"c","text":"traceroute gateway_ip"},{"id":"d","text":"ss -s"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`ip -s link show eth0` displays detailed statistics for the specified interface, including the number of transmitted and received packets, errors, dropped packets, overruns, and frame errors. These counters are essential for diagnosing NIC or driver-level issues. Option A sends ICMP requests and can detect packet loss but does not show hardware-level counters. Option C shows hop-by-hop routing, not interface statistics. Option D shows socket summary statistics, not NIC-level error counters.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ip.8.html","label":"Linux man page: ip"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network-connected Linux server is experiencing intermittent packet loss. The administrator suspects a NIC hardware or driver issue. Which command provides per-interface statistics including error counters such as dropped packets, overruns, and frame errors?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux system running ext4 filesystems fails to boot after an unclean shutdown. The system drops to a maintenance shell and reports that `/dev/sdb1` has filesystem errors. Which command should be used to repair the filesystem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"fsck -y /dev/sdb1"},{"id":"b","text":"mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1"},{"id":"c","text":"mount -o remount,rw /dev/sdb1"},{"id":"d","text":"dd if=/dev/zero of=/dev/sdb1 bs=512 count=1"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`fsck -y /dev/sdb1` runs the filesystem consistency check tool on the specified partition and automatically answers 'yes' to all repair prompts, making it appropriate for unattended recovery. `fsck` must be run on an unmounted or read-only mounted partition, which is typically satisfied in emergency/maintenance mode. Option B (`mkfs.ext4`) reformats the partition, destroying all data. Option C remounts the filesystem read-write without fixing errors. Option D overwrites the partition's boot sector, which would cause data loss.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/fsck.8.html","label":"Linux man page: fsck"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/fsck.ext4.8.html","label":"Linux man page: fsck.ext4"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P2$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux system running ext4 filesystems fails to boot after an unclean shutdown. The system drops to a maintenance shell and reports that `/dev/sdb1` has filesystem errors. Which command should be used to repair the filesystem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user's cron job is not executing at the scheduled time. The cron daemon is running and the crontab syntax has been verified as correct. The administrator checks `/var/log/cron` and sees the job is being triggered, but no output is produced and the expected files are not created. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The cron daemon does not load the user's PATH environment variable, causing commands to not be found"},{"id":"b","text":"The crontab file has incorrect line endings (CRLF instead of LF)"},{"id":"c","text":"The system clock is set to UTC and the cron job is using local time"},{"id":"d","text":"The user's account is locked, preventing cron from running jobs"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Cron executes jobs in a minimal environment that does not inherit the user's interactive shell PATH. Commands like `python`, `node`, or custom scripts that rely on `~/.bashrc` or `/etc/profile` PATH entries will fail silently (or produce 'command not found' in output if MAILTO is set). The fix is to either specify full absolute paths in the crontab or define `PATH=` at the top of the crontab file. CRLF line endings would typically prevent the crontab from loading at all. Time zone mismatches shift execution time but do not prevent execution. A locked account would typically cause cron to log an authentication failure, not silently succeed.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"crontab man page - Linux man-pages"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user's cron job is not executing at the scheduled time. The cron daemon is running and the crontab syntax has been verified as correct. The administrator checks `/var/log/cron` and sees the job is being triggered, but no output is produced and the expected files are not created. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default target so the system boots into a graphical desktop environment instead of the command-line interface. Which command achieves this persistently across reboots?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl set-default graphical.target"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl isolate graphical.target"},{"id":"c","text":"telinit 5"},{"id":"d","text":"update-rc.d graphical defaults"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'systemctl set-default graphical.target' creates a symlink at /etc/systemd/system/default.target pointing to graphical.target, making the change persistent across reboots. 'systemctl isolate graphical.target' only switches the current session without persisting. 'telinit 5' is a legacy SysV init command and does not persist across reboots on systemd-based systems. 'update-rc.d' is a Debian SysV init utility unrelated to setting default systemd targets.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/systemd#Change_default_target_to_boot_into","label":"systemd - ArchWiki: Targets"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_basic_system_settings/working-with-systemd-targets_configuring-basic-system-settings","label":"Red Hat - systemctl set-default"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default target so the system boots into a graphical desktop environment instead of the command-line interface. Which command achieves this persistently across reboots?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to display the UUID of all block devices on a Linux system to update /etc/fstab. Which command provides this information?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"fdisk -l"},{"id":"b","text":"blkid"},{"id":"c","text":"lsblk -f"},{"id":"d","text":"df -h"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'blkid' is the purpose-built command for printing block device attributes, including UUID, filesystem type, and labels. 'lsblk -f' also shows filesystem information and UUIDs, but 'blkid' is the canonical tool specifically designed for this purpose and is typically the best answer in exam contexts for retrieving UUIDs. 'fdisk -l' shows partition table information but not UUIDs. 'df -h' only reports disk space usage for mounted filesystems and provides no UUID information.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/blkid.8.html","label":"Linux man page: blkid"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ Study Guide - Storage Management"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to display the UUID of all block devices on a Linux system to update /etc/fstab. Which command provides this information?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems administrator needs to schedule a recurring job that runs a backup script every day at 2:30 AM for the root user. Which cron expression correctly represents this schedule?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"30 2 * * * /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"b","text":"2 30 * * * /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"c","text":"* * 2 30 * /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"d","text":"0 2 30 * * /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Cron fields are ordered: minute, hour, day-of-month, month, day-of-week. For 2:30 AM daily, the correct expression is '30 2 * * *' — minute 30, hour 2, every day, every month, every day of the week. Option B reverses minute and hour. Option C places values in the day-of-month and month fields. Option D specifies midnight (0 minute, hour 2) on the 30th of each month, not 2:30 AM daily.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"Linux man page: crontab(5)"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/automating_system_tasks/assembly_scheduling-tasks-using-cron_automating-system-tasks","label":"Red Hat - Scheduling tasks with cron"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems administrator needs to schedule a recurring job that runs a backup script every day at 2:30 AM for the root user. Which cron expression correctly represents this schedule?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator runs 'df -h' and notices that the /var partition is at 95% capacity. After investigation, they find that the /var/log directory contains numerous large, uncompressed log files. Which command would the administrator use to find the ten largest files within /var/log, sorted by size in descending order?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ls -lhS /var/log | head -10"},{"id":"b","text":"du -ah /var/log | sort -rh | head -10"},{"id":"c","text":"find /var/log -type f -size +1M"},{"id":"d","text":"stat /var/log/* | grep Size | sort -n"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'du -ah /var/log | sort -rh | head -10' recursively calculates disk usage for all files (-a) in human-readable format (-h), sorts them in reverse human-readable order (largest first), and limits output to the top ten. 'ls -lhS' only lists the immediate directory contents sorted by size but does not recurse into subdirectories. 'find /var/log -type f -size +1M' lists files over 1 MB but does not sort them by size. 'stat' can show file sizes but the pipeline shown is fragile, does not recurse, and does not produce a clean sorted-by-size result.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/du.1.html","label":"Linux man page: du(1)"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/sort.1.html","label":"Linux man page: sort(1)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator runs 'df -h' and notices that the /var partition is at 95% capacity. After investigation, they find that the /var/log directory contains numerous large, uncompressed log files. Which command would the administrator use to find the ten largest files within /var/log, sorted by size in descending order?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to add a new 10 GB logical volume named 'data_lv' to an existing volume group named 'vg_storage'. Which sequence of commands is correct?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"vgcreate vg_storage /dev/sdb1 && lvcreate -L 10G -n data_lv vg_storage"},{"id":"b","text":"lvcreate -L 10G -n data_lv vg_storage"},{"id":"c","text":"pvcreate /dev/sdb1 && lvcreate -L 10G -n data_lv /dev/sdb1"},{"id":"d","text":"vgextend vg_storage /dev/sdb1 && mkfs.ext4 /dev/vg_storage/data_lv"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Because the volume group 'vg_storage' already exists and has sufficient free space, only 'lvcreate -L 10G -n data_lv vg_storage' is needed to create a 10 GB logical volume named data_lv within it. Option A incorrectly attempts to create the volume group again with 'vgcreate', which would fail on an existing VG. Option C uses 'pvcreate' and then passes a physical device directly to 'lvcreate', which is incorrect syntax — lvcreate takes a VG name, not a PV path. Option D extends the VG with a new PV and then formats a device that does not yet exist (lvcreate was never called).$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lvcreate.8.html","label":"Linux man page: lvcreate(8)"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_logical_volumes/index","label":"Red Hat - Logical Volume Manager Administration"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to add a new 10 GB logical volume named 'data_lv' to an existing volume group named 'vg_storage'. Which sequence of commands is correct?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator wants to ensure that the 'httpd' service starts automatically at boot and is also started immediately without rebooting the system. Which single command accomplishes both actions simultaneously?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl start httpd && systemctl enable httpd"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl enable --now httpd"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl daemon-reload && systemctl start httpd"},{"id":"d","text":"service httpd start && chkconfig httpd on"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'systemctl enable --now httpd' is the most efficient single command that both enables the service for automatic startup at boot (by creating the appropriate symlink) AND immediately starts it in the current session. Option A achieves the same result but uses two separate commands joined by a shell operator, not a single command. Option C reloads the systemd manager configuration and starts the service but does not enable it for boot. Option D uses legacy SysV init tools ('service' and 'chkconfig') that, while functional on some systems, are not the current systemd standard and do not constitute a single command.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemctl.html","label":"systemd.io - systemctl enable --now"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_basic_system_settings/managing-system-services-with-systemctl_configuring-basic-system-settings","label":"Red Hat - Managing services with systemctl"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator wants to ensure that the 'httpd' service starts automatically at boot and is also started immediately without rebooting the system. Which single command accomplishes both actions simultaneously?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to modify kernel parameters at runtime to disable IPv6 on all network interfaces without rebooting the system. Which command correctly applies this change?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"sysctl -w net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6=1"},{"id":"b","text":"echo 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv6/conf/all/disable_ipv6"},{"id":"c","text":"modprobe -r ipv6"},{"id":"d","text":"ip link set all disable ipv6"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'sysctl -w net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6=1' is the standard, recommended method for modifying kernel parameters at runtime using the sysctl interface. It writes directly to the appropriate /proc/sys path in a safe, documented manner. Option B writing directly to /proc/sys achieves the same immediate effect, but it bypasses the sysctl abstraction layer and is not considered best practice for administration. Option C attempts to remove the IPv6 kernel module, which may fail if IPv6 is built into the kernel (not compiled as a module) and is a more disruptive approach. Option D ('ip link set all disable ipv6') is not a valid 'ip' command syntax and will produce an error.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/sysctl.8.html","label":"Linux man page: sysctl(8)"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_monitoring_and_updating_the_kernel/configuring-kernel-parameters-at-runtime_managing-monitoring-and-updating-the-kernel","label":"Red Hat - Configuring kernel parameters at runtime"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to modify kernel parameters at runtime to disable IPv6 on all network interfaces without rebooting the system. Which command correctly applies this change?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to configure the system so that all SUID and SGID binaries are identified on a mounted filesystem at /data. Which command will correctly locate all files with the SUID or SGID bit set on that filesystem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"find /data -perm /6000 -type f"},{"id":"b","text":"ls -lR /data | grep 's'"},{"id":"c","text":"stat /data -c '%A %n'"},{"id":"d","text":"find /data -perm 777 -type f"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'find /data -perm /6000 -type f' searches for regular files where either the SUID bit (4000) or SGID bit (2000) is set. The /6000 syntax (using a forward slash) means 'match if ANY of these bits are set.' Option b (ls -lR with grep) is unreliable and not scriptable for security auditing. Option c (stat) reports on a single path and does not search recursively. Option d (-perm 777) finds files with full read/write/execute permissions for all users, which has nothing to do with SUID/SGID bits.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/findutils/manual/html_mono/find.html#Symbolic-Modes","label":"GNU find manual – Symbolic Modes and Permission Bits"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to configure the system so that all SUID and SGID binaries are identified on a mounted filesystem at /data. Which command will correctly locate all files with the SUID or SGID bit set on that filesystem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to ensure that the SSH daemon on a Linux server does not allow root login and does not permit password-based authentication, allowing only key-based authentication. Which two directives must be set in /etc/ssh/sshd_config to enforce this policy? (Choose the single option that correctly represents BOTH required directives.)$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"PermitRootLogin no  and  PasswordAuthentication no"},{"id":"b","text":"PermitRootLogin no  and  PubkeyAuthentication no"},{"id":"c","text":"AllowRootLogin no  and  PasswordAuthentication no"},{"id":"d","text":"PermitRootLogin no  and  ChallengeResponseAuthentication yes"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'PermitRootLogin no' prevents the root account from authenticating over SSH entirely, and 'PasswordAuthentication no' forces all users to use key-based authentication by disabling password logins. Option b is wrong because setting 'PubkeyAuthentication no' would disable key-based authentication, which is the opposite of the desired outcome. Option c is wrong because 'AllowRootLogin' is not a valid sshd_config directive; the correct directive is 'PermitRootLogin'. Option d is wrong because enabling 'ChallengeResponseAuthentication yes' still allows a form of interactive password-like authentication (e.g., PAM-based), which does not satisfy the key-only requirement.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man.openbsd.org/sshd_config","label":"OpenSSH sshd_config man page"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/securing_networks/assembly_using-secure-communications-between-two-systems-with-openssh_securing-networks","label":"Red Hat – Configuring OpenSSH"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to ensure that the SSH daemon on a Linux server does not allow root login and does not permit password-based authentication, allowing only key-based authentication. Which two directives must be set in /etc/ssh/sshd_config to enforce this policy? (Choose the single option that correctly represents BOTH required directives.)$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer is hardening a Linux server and wants to use AppArmor to confine a web application process. The engineer has written a new AppArmor profile stored at /etc/apparmor.d/usr.sbin.webapp. Which command loads this profile and immediately places it into enforce mode?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"apparmor_parser -r /etc/apparmor.d/usr.sbin.webapp"},{"id":"b","text":"aa-complain /etc/apparmor.d/usr.sbin.webapp"},{"id":"c","text":"apparmor_parser -C /etc/apparmor.d/usr.sbin.webapp"},{"id":"d","text":"aa-status --enforce /etc/apparmor.d/usr.sbin.webapp"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'apparmor_parser -r' reads and loads (or reloads) a profile into the kernel in enforce mode by default. This is the standard way to activate a new or updated AppArmor profile immediately. Option b (aa-complain) places the profile in complain/learning mode, which only logs violations rather than blocking them — the opposite of enforce mode. Option c uses the '-C' flag, which also loads the profile in complain mode, not enforce mode. Option d is incorrect because 'aa-status' is a read-only tool used to display the current status of AppArmor profiles; it does not load profiles and does not accept an '--enforce' flag.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://ubuntu.com/server/docs/apparmor","label":"Ubuntu AppArmor Documentation"},{"url":"https://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/noble/man8/apparmor_parser.8.html","label":"apparmor_parser man page (Ubuntu Manpages)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer is hardening a Linux server and wants to use AppArmor to confine a web application process. The engineer has written a new AppArmor profile stored at /etc/apparmor.d/usr.sbin.webapp. Which command loads this profile and immediately places it into enforce mode?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator is reviewing the /etc/sudoers file to audit privilege escalation rules. One line in the file reads:

  %developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2

What does this line specifically allow?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Members of the 'developers' group can restart the apache2 service using systemctl on any host without being prompted for a password."},{"id":"b","text":"The user named 'developers' can run any command as any user on all hosts without a password."},{"id":"c","text":"Members of the 'developers' group can run any systemctl command without a password on localhost only."},{"id":"d","text":"Members of the 'developers' group must provide the root password to restart the apache2 service."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$In sudoers syntax, a leading '%' denotes a group name, so '%developers' refers to the Unix group 'developers', not a user. 'ALL=(ALL)' means the rule applies on all hosts and the command can be run as any user. 'NOPASSWD:' waives the password prompt. The command is restricted to '/usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2' only — not all systemctl commands. Option b is wrong because '%developers' is a group, not a user named 'developers', and the allowed command is restricted. Option c is wrong because the rule applies to ALL hosts (not just localhost) and is restricted to one specific systemctl command. Option d is wrong because NOPASSWD explicitly removes any password requirement.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.sudo.ws/docs/man/sudoers.man/","label":"sudoers man page (sudo.ws)"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_basic_system_settings/managing-sudo-access_configuring-basic-system-settings","label":"Red Hat – Configuring sudo"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator is reviewing the /etc/sudoers file to audit privilege escalation rules. One line in the file reads:

  %developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2

What does this line specifically allow?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to use firewalld to permanently block all inbound traffic to TCP port 23 (Telnet) on the 'public' zone, and ensure the rule survives a reboot. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=telnet --permanent && firewall-cmd --reload"},{"id":"b","text":"firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-port=23/tcp --permanent && firewall-cmd --reload"},{"id":"c","text":"iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 23 -j DROP && service iptables save"},{"id":"d","text":"firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-port=23/tcp && firewall-cmd --reload"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Since Telnet is a named service in firewalld, the correct and idiomatic approach is to use '--remove-service=telnet' to ensure the Telnet service definition (port 23/tcp) is blocked. Adding '--permanent' writes the rule to the persistent configuration, and '--reload' applies it to the running configuration without a reboot. Option b is wrong because '--add-port=23/tcp' would OPEN port 23, the opposite of blocking it. Option c is wrong because mixing iptables commands with firewalld is unsupported and can cause conflicts; firewalld manages iptables/nftables as a backend and direct iptables rules may be flushed by firewalld. Option d omits '--permanent', meaning the rule will not persist across reboots or firewalld reloads.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_firewalls_and_packet_filters/using-and-configuring-firewalld_firewall-packet-filters","label":"Red Hat – Using and Configuring firewalld"},{"url":"https://firewalld.org/documentation/man-pages/firewall-cmd.html","label":"firewall-cmd man page (firewalld.org)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to use firewalld to permanently block all inbound traffic to TCP port 23 (Telnet) on the 'public' zone, and ensure the rule survives a reboot. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator is writing a Bash script that processes a list of server hostnames stored in a file called `servers.txt`. The script should iterate over each hostname and print a message only if the hostname starts with the prefix `web-`. Which of the following script snippets correctly accomplishes this task?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"while read host; do\n  if [[ \"$host\" == web-* ]]; then\n    echo \"Web server found: $host\"\n  fi\ndone < servers.txt"},{"id":"b","text":"for host in servers.txt; do\n  if [ \"$host\" -eq \"web-*\" ]; then\n    echo \"Web server found: $host\"\n  fi\ndone"},{"id":"c","text":"while read host; do\n  if [ \"$host\" == \"web-*\" ]; then\n    echo \"Web server found: $host\"\n  fi\ndone < servers.txt"},{"id":"d","text":"for host in $(servers.txt); do\n  if [[ \"$host\" =~ web-* ]]; then\n    echo \"Web server found: $host\"\n  fi\ndone"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because it uses `while read host; do ... done < servers.txt` to properly read each line of the file into the variable `$host`, and the double-bracket conditional `[[ "$host" == web-* ]]` correctly performs a glob pattern match to check if the hostname starts with `web-`. The double brackets `[[ ]]` support glob-style pattern matching natively without quoting the wildcard. Option B is incorrect for two reasons: `for host in servers.txt` iterates over the literal string 'servers.txt' rather than its contents, and `-eq` is an arithmetic operator, not a string comparison. Option C is incorrect because inside single brackets `[ ]`, the `==` operator with a wildcard like `web-*` treats it as a literal string rather than a glob pattern, so the match will never succeed as intended. Option D is incorrect because `$(servers.txt)` attempts to execute `servers.txt` as a command rather than reading the file's contents; additionally, `=~` is for extended regular expression matching, and `web-*` is not a valid ERE (it would need to be `web-.*` or `^web-`).$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Conditional-Constructs","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Conditional Constructs"},{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Pattern-Matching","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Pattern Matching"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ (XK0-005) Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator is writing a Bash script that processes a list of server hostnames stored in a file called `servers.txt`. The script should iterate over each hostname and print a message only if the hostname starts with the prefix `web-`. Which of the following script snippets correctly accomplishes this task?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a server's root filesystem is reporting 100% disk usage, but `du -sh /*` shows only 60% of the expected data. Which command would BEST help identify files that are deleted but still held open by a running process, consuming the unreported space?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"lsof | grep '(deleted)'"},{"id":"b","text":"find / -size +100M -type f"},{"id":"c","text":"df -ih"},{"id":"d","text":"fdisk -l /dev/sda"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a file is deleted while a process still has it open, the filesystem marks the inode as deleted but the space is not released until the file descriptor is closed. `lsof | grep '(deleted)'` lists all open file descriptors flagged as deleted, revealing the processes holding the space. `find` only shows existing files; `df -ih` shows inode usage, not deleted-but-open files; `fdisk -l` shows partition information.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lsof.8.html","label":"lsof man page (The Linux man-pages project)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a server's root filesystem is reporting 100% disk usage, but `du -sh /*` shows only 60% of the expected data. Which command would BEST help identify files that are deleted but still held open by a running process, consuming the unreported space?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a recent kernel update, a system fails to boot and drops into emergency mode. The administrator suspects a broken initramfs image. Which command should be run from a rescue environment to regenerate the initramfs for the currently installed kernel on a RHEL-based system?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"update-initramfs -u -k all"},{"id":"b","text":"dracut --force /boot/initramfs-$(uname -r).img $(uname -r)"},{"id":"c","text":"grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg"},{"id":"d","text":"mkinitrd --force /boot/initrd.img"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`dracut --force` is the correct tool for regenerating an initramfs on RHEL/CentOS/Fedora-based systems. The `--force` flag overwrites an existing image. `update-initramfs` is the Debian/Ubuntu equivalent. `grub2-mkconfig` regenerates the GRUB configuration file, not the initramfs. `mkinitrd` is an older, largely deprecated tool and the syntax shown is incomplete.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_monitoring_and_updating_the_kernel/assembly_making-persistent-changes-to-the-initramfs_managing-monitoring-and-updating-the-kernel","label":"dracut - Red Hat Customer Portal"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a recent kernel update, a system fails to boot and drops into emergency mode. The administrator suspects a broken initramfs image. Which command should be run from a rescue environment to regenerate the initramfs for the currently installed kernel on a RHEL-based system?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A junior administrator reports that a critical service daemon is failing to start and the error message reads: `bind: Permission denied` on port 443. SELinux is enforcing. Which command will BEST confirm whether SELinux is blocking the service from binding to that port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ausearch -m avc -ts recent"},{"id":"b","text":"ss -tlnp | grep 443"},{"id":"c","text":"getenforce"},{"id":"d","text":"cat /var/log/messages | grep denied"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`ausearch -m avc -ts recent` queries the audit log for recent Access Vector Cache (AVC) denial events, which are produced when SELinux blocks an action such as a service binding to a port. `ss -tlnp` shows currently listening ports but does not reveal SELinux denials. `getenforce` only reports the current SELinux mode. Grepping `/var/log/messages` may miss AVC events that are only written to the audit log.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://linux.die.net/man/8/ausearch","label":"ausearch - Linux Audit Documentation"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/using_selinux/troubleshooting-problems-related-to-selinux_using-selinux","label":"Understanding SELinux AVC Denials - Red Hat"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A junior administrator reports that a critical service daemon is failing to start and the error message reads: `bind: Permission denied` on port 443. SELinux is enforcing. Which command will BEST confirm whether SELinux is blocking the service from binding to that port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator is troubleshooting high CPU wait (wa) values consistently above 30% as shown by `top`. The system has multiple disk-heavy processes. Which tool provides per-device I/O statistics including read/write throughput and await times to help pinpoint the bottleneck?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"vmstat 1 5"},{"id":"b","text":"iostat -xz 1 5"},{"id":"c","text":"sar -u 1 5"},{"id":"d","text":"netstat -s"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`iostat -xz 1 5` provides extended statistics (-x) per block device, suppressing devices with no activity (-z), sampled every second for five intervals. It shows `await` (average I/O wait time) and `%util` (device saturation), which directly identifies the bottleneck. `vmstat` shows aggregate I/O but not per-device detail. `sar -u` reports CPU statistics. `netstat -s` shows network protocol statistics.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/iostat.1.html","label":"iostat man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator is troubleshooting high CPU wait (wa) values consistently above 30% as shown by `top`. The system has multiple disk-heavy processes. Which tool provides per-device I/O statistics including read/write throughput and await times to help pinpoint the bottleneck?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a network interface `eth1` that is physically connected but shows no IP address after a reboot on a system using NetworkManager. Which command will display the current connection profile status and help determine why the interface did not come up automatically?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"nmcli connection show"},{"id":"b","text":"ip link show eth1"},{"id":"c","text":"ifconfig eth1"},{"id":"d","text":"ethtool eth1"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`nmcli connection show` lists all NetworkManager connection profiles with their state (activated/deactivated) and the interface they are bound to. It reveals whether a profile exists for `eth1` and if `autoconnect` is disabled, explaining why no IP was assigned. `ip link show` shows link state but not profile configuration. `ifconfig eth1` shows current IP state but not configuration profiles. `ethtool eth1` shows physical/hardware properties.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://networkmanager.dev/docs/api/latest/nmcli.html","label":"nmcli man page - NetworkManager"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a network interface `eth1` that is physically connected but shows no IP address after a reboot on a system using NetworkManager. Which command will display the current connection profile status and help determine why the interface did not come up automatically?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer reports that a Python application segfaults randomly. The administrator wants to capture a core dump for post-mortem analysis. After setting `ulimit -c unlimited`, in which default location will the core dump file be written on most modern systemd-based Linux systems?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/tmp/core"},{"id":"b","text":"/var/lib/systemd/coredump/"},{"id":"c","text":"The current working directory of the crashing process"},{"id":"d","text":"/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$On systemd-based systems, `systemd-coredump` intercepts core dumps via the `kernel.core_pattern` sysctl and stores them in `/var/lib/systemd/coredump/` (compressed). Administrators can inspect them with `coredumpctl`. On non-systemd systems, the core is written to the process's working directory if `core_pattern` is not redirected. `/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern` is a sysctl file that configures the pattern, not a storage location.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-coredump.html","label":"systemd-coredump - freedesktop.org"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
