  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer reports that a Python application segfaults randomly. The administrator wants to capture a core dump for post-mortem analysis. After setting `ulimit -c unlimited`, in which default location will the core dump file be written on most modern systemd-based Linux systems?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$While reviewing system logs, an administrator sees repeated journal entries: `kernel: EXT4-fs error (device sdb1): ext4_find_entry: reading directory lblock 0`. What is the MOST appropriate next step to investigate and repair the filesystem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Run `fsck.ext4 -y /dev/sdb1` after unmounting the device"},{"id":"b","text":"Run `tune2fs -l /dev/sdb1` to read superblock information"},{"id":"c","text":"Remount the filesystem read-write to auto-correct errors"},{"id":"d","text":"Run `badblocks -sv /dev/sdb1` without unmounting"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$EXT4 directory read errors indicate filesystem corruption. `fsck.ext4 -y /dev/sdb1` (run unmounted) performs a filesystem check and automatically answers 'yes' to repair prompts. The filesystem MUST be unmounted first to avoid further corruption. `tune2fs -l` only reads metadata, it does not repair. Remounting read-write on a corrupted filesystem can worsen damage. `badblocks` checks for bad sectors but must not be run on a mounted filesystem, and it does not repair directory entries.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/fsck.ext4.8.html","label":"fsck.ext4 man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$While reviewing system logs, an administrator sees repeated journal entries: `kernel: EXT4-fs error (device sdb1): ext4_find_entry: reading directory lblock 0`. What is the MOST appropriate next step to investigate and repair the filesystem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systemd service named `appd.service` fails to start. Running `systemctl start appd.service` returns `Failed to start appd.service: Unit not found`. Which command provides the MOST detailed output to diagnose why the unit file cannot be located or loaded?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"journalctl -xe"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl status appd.service"},{"id":"c","text":"systemd-analyze verify appd.service"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl daemon-reload && systemctl list-unit-files"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`systemd-analyze verify appd.service` parses the unit file (or checks for its absence) and reports syntax errors, missing dependencies, and configuration issues before attempting to start it. This is the most targeted tool for unit file problems. `journalctl -xe` shows runtime journal errors but won't help if the unit file is simply absent or malformed before loading. `systemctl status` also reports the unit-not-found error but provides less diagnostic detail on why. `daemon-reload` refreshes the manager but does not diagnose the root cause.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-analyze.html","label":"systemd-analyze - freedesktop.org"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systemd service named `appd.service` fails to start. Running `systemctl start appd.service` returns `Failed to start appd.service: Unit not found`. Which command provides the MOST detailed output to diagnose why the unit file cannot be located or loaded?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator observes that SSH connections to a remote host are taking over 30 seconds to establish but eventually succeed. Which SSH client-side option, added to `~/.ssh/config`, will MOST likely resolve the delay caused by reverse DNS lookup timeouts on the server?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"AddKeysToAgent yes"},{"id":"b","text":"ConnectTimeout 5"},{"id":"c","text":"GSSAPIAuthentication no"},{"id":"d","text":"ServerAliveInterval 15"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Slow SSH logins that eventually succeed are a classic symptom of either GSSAPI (Kerberos) authentication probing or reverse DNS lookup delays. `GSSAPIAuthentication no` disables the GSSAPI negotiation on the client side, which is a very common cause of 20-30 second SSH delays in environments without Kerberos. On the server side, `UseDNS no` in `sshd_config` resolves reverse-DNS delays. `ConnectTimeout 5` would cause the connection to fail, not speed it up. `AddKeysToAgent` and `ServerAliveInterval` do not affect the login delay.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/ssh_config.5.html","label":"ssh_config man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator observes that SSH connections to a remote host are taking over 30 seconds to establish but eventually succeed. Which SSH client-side option, added to `~/.ssh/config`, will MOST likely resolve the delay caused by reverse DNS lookup timeouts on the server?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user reports they cannot write to a directory `/data/shared` even though `ls -ld /data/shared` shows permissions `drwxrwxrwx` and they are listed in the correct group. Which command will BEST determine if an ACL is overriding the standard permissions?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"stat /data/shared"},{"id":"b","text":"getfacl /data/shared"},{"id":"c","text":"ls -la /data/shared"},{"id":"d","text":"chmod -R 777 /data/shared"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`getfacl /data/shared` displays the POSIX ACL entries for the directory, including any named user or group deny entries and the ACL mask that may restrict effective permissions. When `ls -l` shows a `+` after the permission bits, ACLs are present and may override standard mode bits. `stat` shows inode metadata but not ACL detail. `ls -la` does not show ACL contents. `chmod -R 777` is destructive and does not diagnose the issue.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/getfacl.1.html","label":"getfacl man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user reports they cannot write to a directory `/data/shared` even though `ls -ld /data/shared` shows permissions `drwxrwxrwx` and they are listed in the correct group. Which command will BEST determine if an ACL is overriding the standard permissions?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A newly deployed application server is intermittently unable to resolve external hostnames despite having a valid `/etc/resolv.conf`. The administrator suspects that the Name Service Switch (NSS) configuration may be routing lookups incorrectly. Which file should be examined to verify the order in which hostname resolution sources are queried?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/hosts"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/resolv.conf"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/nsswitch.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"/etc/systemd/resolved.conf"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`/etc/nsswitch.conf` defines the order and sources for various name resolution databases including `hosts`. A typical entry like `hosts: files dns` means `/etc/hosts` is checked first, then DNS. A misconfigured entry such as `hosts: files` would cause DNS to be skipped entirely, explaining intermittent failures. `/etc/hosts` contains static hostname mappings. `/etc/resolv.conf` lists DNS server addresses. `/etc/systemd/resolved.conf` configures the systemd-resolved stub resolver but does not control NSS ordering.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/nsswitch.conf.5.html","label":"nsswitch.conf man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A newly deployed application server is intermittently unable to resolve external hostnames despite having a valid `/etc/resolv.conf`. The administrator suspects that the Name Service Switch (NSS) configuration may be routing lookups incorrectly. Which file should be examined to verify the order in which hostname resolution sources are queried?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During troubleshooting, an administrator runs `ss -s` and notices a very high number of sockets in TIME_WAIT state. Which kernel parameter, tunable via `sysctl`, allows the reuse of TIME_WAIT sockets for new outbound connections to reduce socket exhaustion?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"net.ipv4.tcp_fin_timeout"},{"id":"b","text":"net.ipv4.tcp_tw_reuse"},{"id":"c","text":"net.core.somaxconn"},{"id":"d","text":"net.ipv4.ip_local_port_range"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`net.ipv4.tcp_tw_reuse` when set to `1` allows the kernel to reuse a socket in TIME_WAIT state for a new outbound TCP connection if the connection is from the same source port to the same remote address/port, reducing ephemeral port exhaustion. `net.ipv4.tcp_fin_timeout` controls the time a socket stays in FIN_WAIT_2. `net.core.somaxconn` sets the maximum listen backlog. `net.ipv4.ip_local_port_range` sets the ephemeral port range but does not enable reuse of TIME_WAIT sockets.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/latest/networking/ip-sysctl.html","label":"Linux kernel networking parameters - ip-sysctl"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During troubleshooting, an administrator runs `ss -s` and notices a very high number of sockets in TIME_WAIT state. Which kernel parameter, tunable via `sysctl`, allows the reuse of TIME_WAIT sockets for new outbound connections to reduce socket exhaustion?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to trace all system calls made by a running process with PID 4521 to diagnose unexpected behavior without stopping the process. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"strace -p 4521"},{"id":"b","text":"ltrace -p 4521"},{"id":"c","text":"perf stat -p 4521"},{"id":"d","text":"gdb --pid 4521"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`strace -p 4521` attaches to the running process and prints all system calls it makes in real time, without stopping it. This is essential for diagnosing issues like unexpected file access, failed socket calls, or permission errors. `ltrace` traces library calls (not system calls). `perf stat` collects performance counter statistics, not system call traces. `gdb --pid` attaches a debugger, which pauses the process and is more invasive.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/strace.1.html","label":"strace man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to trace all system calls made by a running process with PID 4521 to diagnose unexpected behavior without stopping the process. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A server's `/var` partition fills up unexpectedly overnight. After freeing space, the administrator wants to identify which process or service is writing large amounts of data to `/var` in real time. Which tool provides per-process disk I/O statistics to identify the culprit?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"iotop -ao"},{"id":"b","text":"df -h /var"},{"id":"c","text":"du -sh /var/*"},{"id":"d","text":"watch ls -lh /var/log"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`iotop -ao` runs iotop in accumulated mode (-a) showing only processes that are actively doing I/O (-o), making it easy to identify which process has written the most data. `df -h /var` shows overall partition usage but not which process is writing. `du -sh /var/*` shows directory sizes at a point in time, not real-time write activity. `watch ls -lh /var/log` polls file sizes but cannot attribute writes to a specific process.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/iotop.8.html","label":"iotop man page"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A server's `/var` partition fills up unexpectedly overnight. After freeing space, the administrator wants to identify which process or service is writing large amounts of data to `/var` in real time. Which tool provides per-process disk I/O statistics to identify the culprit?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After adding a new static route with `ip route add 192.168.50.0/24 via 10.0.0.1`, the administrator confirms the route is present in the routing table. However, after a reboot the route is gone. What is the MOST appropriate action to make the route persistent on a system using NetworkManager?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Add the route to `/etc/rc.local`"},{"id":"b","text":"Use `nmcli connection modify <profile> +ipv4.routes '192.168.50.0/24 10.0.0.1'` and then activate the connection"},{"id":"c","text":"Add the `ip route add` command to `/etc/profile`"},{"id":"d","text":"Set `PERSISTENT_ROUTES=yes` in `/etc/sysconfig/network`"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$On NetworkManager-managed systems, persistent static routes must be stored in the connection profile using `nmcli connection modify`. NM writes the route into the profile configuration and re-applies it every time the connection is activated. `/etc/rc.local` is a legacy method that is not guaranteed to execute at the right time and is not managed by NM. Adding the command to `/etc/profile` only runs for interactive shells. `PERSISTENT_ROUTES=yes` is not a valid directive in modern RHEL-based network configuration.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_networking/configuring-static-routes_configuring-and-managing-networking","label":"Configuring static routes with nmcli - Red Hat Documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P3$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After adding a new static route with `ip route add 192.168.50.0/24 via 10.0.0.1`, the administrator confirms the route is present in the routing table. However, after a reboot the route is gone. What is the MOST appropriate action to make the route persistent on a system using NetworkManager?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A batch job script that previously ran successfully now fails with 'Permission denied' when attempting to write output files to `/data/reports/`. The directory permissions show `drwxrwsr-x` and are owned by `root:reports`. The service account running the job is a member of the `reports` group. SELinux is enforcing on this system. What should the administrator check FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Verify the service account's UID and GID with `id <username>`"},{"id":"b","text":"Check SELinux denials in the audit log using `ausearch -m avc -ts recent`"},{"id":"c","text":"Recursively reset permissions on `/data/reports/` with `chmod -R 777`"},{"id":"d","text":"Run `chcon -R --type=tmp_t /data/reports/` to relabel the directory"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Since the directory has appropriate DAC (discretionary access control) permissions for group `reports` and the user is a member of that group, the likely culprit is an SELinux AVC (Access Vector Cache) denial. On SELinux-enforcing systems, even if POSIX permissions allow access, SELinux policy can still block the operation. `ausearch -m avc -ts recent` searches the audit log for recent AVC denial messages, which will confirm whether SELinux is the cause and identify the specific context mismatch. Option a is a reasonable secondary check but the permissions already appear correct for group access. Option c is a poor practice that removes security controls. Option d applies the `tmp_t` context which is inappropriate for a reports directory and could make things worse.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ausearch.8.html","label":"ausearch man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/using_selinux/troubleshooting-problems-related-to-selinux_using-selinux","label":"Red Hat – Troubleshooting SELinux"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A batch job script that previously ran successfully now fails with 'Permission denied' when attempting to write output files to `/data/reports/`. The directory permissions show `drwxrwsr-x` and are owned by `root:reports`. The service account running the job is a member of the `reports` group. SELinux is enforcing on this system. What should the administrator check FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server's `/var` filesystem is running out of space. An administrator suspects that old systemd journal logs are the primary consumer. Which command will reclaim space by removing journal logs older than 30 days?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"rm -rf /var/log/journal/*"},{"id":"b","text":"journalctl --vacuum-time=30d"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl restart systemd-journald --purge"},{"id":"d","text":"truncate -s 0 /var/log/journal/*.journal"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`journalctl --vacuum-time=30d` is the safe, supported method for removing systemd journal files older than the specified time period. It interacts with the journal daemon properly and respects journal integrity. `rm -rf /var/log/journal/*` (option a) forcibly deletes all journal files including active ones, which can cause corruption or journal loss and bypasses the daemon. `systemctl restart systemd-journald --purge` (option c) is not a valid systemctl syntax and `--purge` is not a recognized flag for this unit. `truncate -s 0` (option d) zeros out journal binary files directly on disk, which corrupts them without recovering space properly through the journal layer.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/journalctl.1.html","label":"journalctl man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd-journald.service.html","label":"systemd-journald – Freedesktop documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server's `/var` filesystem is running out of space. An administrator suspects that old systemd journal logs are the primary consumer. Which command will reclaim space by removing journal logs older than 30 days?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a kernel update, a server fails to boot and drops to an initramfs emergency shell with the error: 'ALERT! /dev/mapper/vg0-root does not exist'. The server uses LVM on top of software RAID. What is the MOST likely cause of this error?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The GRUB bootloader configuration file points to the wrong kernel version"},{"id":"b","text":"The new kernel's initramfs image was not generated with the required LVM and RAID modules"},{"id":"c","text":"The LVM volume group was accidentally deactivated with `vgchange -an`"},{"id":"d","text":"The `/etc/fstab` entry for the root filesystem uses a LABEL instead of a UUID"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When the initramfs does not contain the necessary kernel modules and tools to activate LVM volumes (and assemble RAID arrays if applicable), the device mapper targets will not be created during early boot, resulting in the error '/dev/mapper/vg0-root does not exist'. This is a classic symptom after a kernel update where the initramfs was not properly regenerated for the new kernel using `dracut` or `mkinitrd`. The fix is to boot the old kernel, then regenerate the initramfs with `dracut -f /boot/initramfs-$(uname -r).img $(uname -r)`. Option a (wrong GRUB config) would cause a different error (kernel not found or wrong kernel loaded). Option c would affect a running system, not the boot process before LVM is activated. Option d (LABEL vs UUID) is unrelated to the device mapper not being created.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/dracut.8.html","label":"dracut man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/1958","label":"Red Hat – Regenerating the initramfs image"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a kernel update, a server fails to boot and drops to an initramfs emergency shell with the error: 'ALERT! /dev/mapper/vg0-root does not exist'. The server uses LVM on top of software RAID. What is the MOST likely cause of this error?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default runlevel so that the system boots into multi-user mode without a graphical interface on a systemd-based distribution. Which command should the administrator run to accomplish this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl set-default multi-user.target"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl isolate graphical.target"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl enable multi-user.target"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl default runlevel3.target"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'systemctl set-default multi-user.target' sets the default systemd target that the system boots into. The 'multi-user.target' corresponds to the traditional runlevel 3 — full multi-user mode without a graphical interface. Option B ('isolate') switches the currently running system to a different target immediately but does not persist across reboots. Option C ('enable') makes a service or target start at boot but does not set the default boot target. Option D is not a valid systemctl subcommand syntax.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.target.html","label":"systemd.target — systemd documentation"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default runlevel so that the system boots into multi-user mode without a graphical interface on a systemd-based distribution. Which command should the administrator run to accomplish this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is managing disk quotas on an ext4 filesystem mounted at /home. After enabling quotas in /etc/fstab with the 'usrquota' option and remounting the partition, which sequence of commands correctly initializes and activates user quotas?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"quotacheck -cug /home && quotaon /home"},{"id":"b","text":"quotaon /home && quotacheck -cug /home"},{"id":"c","text":"edquota /home && quotaon -a"},{"id":"d","text":"repquota /home && quotacheck /home"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'quotacheck -cug /home' scans the filesystem to create the quota database files (aquota.user and aquota.group) — the '-c' flag creates the files, '-u' checks user quotas, and '-g' checks group quotas. After the database files exist, 'quotaon /home' activates quota enforcement on that mount point. Option B reverses the order; running quotaon before the quota database files exist will fail. Option C uses 'edquota', which is used to edit individual user quota limits, not initialize the quota system. Option D uses 'repquota', which only generates a quota usage report and does not initialize or activate quotas.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://tldp.org/HOWTO/Quota.html","label":"Linux Disk Quotas — Linux Documentation Project"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/quotacheck.8.html","label":"quotacheck man page — Linux man-pages project"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is managing disk quotas on an ext4 filesystem mounted at /home. After enabling quotas in /etc/fstab with the 'usrquota' option and remounting the partition, which sequence of commands correctly initializes and activates user quotas?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems administrator wants to schedule a job that runs a backup script located at /usr/local/bin/backup.sh every weekday (Monday through Friday) at 2:30 AM. Which crontab entry correctly implements this schedule?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"30 2 * * 1-5 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"b","text":"2 30 * * 1-5 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"c","text":"30 2 * * 0-4 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"d","text":"30 2 1-5 * * /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A crontab entry follows the format: minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week command. To run at 2:30 AM, the minute field is '30' and the hour field is '2'. Day-of-week values 1-5 represent Monday through Friday. Therefore, '30 2 * * 1-5' is correct. Option B incorrectly swaps the minute and hour fields, which would represent 30:02 — an invalid time. Option C uses '0-4' for the day-of-week, which represents Sunday through Thursday (0=Sunday in cron), not Monday through Friday. Option D incorrectly places '1-5' in the day-of-month field rather than the day-of-week field.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"crontab(5) — Linux man-pages project"},{"url":"https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Cron","label":"cron — Arch Linux Wiki"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems administrator wants to schedule a job that runs a backup script located at /usr/local/bin/backup.sh every weekday (Monday through Friday) at 2:30 AM. Which crontab entry correctly implements this schedule?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to permanently add a static route to the 192.168.50.0/24 network via gateway 10.0.0.1 on a RHEL-based system using NetworkManager. Which command achieves this without requiring a manual restart of the network interface?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"nmcli connection modify eth0 +ipv4.routes '192.168.50.0/24 10.0.0.1' && nmcli connection up eth0"},{"id":"b","text":"ip route add 192.168.50.0/24 via 10.0.0.1 dev eth0"},{"id":"c","text":"route add -net 192.168.50.0/24 gw 10.0.0.1 dev eth0"},{"id":"d","text":"echo '192.168.50.0/24 via 10.0.0.1' >> /etc/sysconfig/network"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'nmcli connection modify' updates the NetworkManager connection profile to include the static route persistently, and 'nmcli connection up eth0' reactivates the connection to apply the change immediately — all without a full network service restart. Option B ('ip route add') adds a route to the live kernel routing table only; it does not survive a reboot or network restart because it does not modify any persistent configuration. Option C ('route add') uses the deprecated net-tools utility and also only modifies the live routing table non-persistently. Option D appends to /etc/sysconfig/network, which is not the correct file format for per-interface static routes on RHEL-based systems and will not work as intended.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_networking/configuring-static-routes_configuring-and-managing-networking","label":"Configuring static routes with nmcli — Red Hat Documentation"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/nmcli.1.html","label":"nmcli(1) — Linux man-pages project"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to permanently add a static route to the 192.168.50.0/24 network via gateway 10.0.0.1 on a RHEL-based system using NetworkManager. Which command achieves this without requiring a manual restart of the network interface?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to ensure that no user can log in as root directly via SSH. Which configuration directive in '/etc/ssh/sshd_config' should be set to achieve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"PermitRootLogin no"},{"id":"b","text":"DenyUsers root"},{"id":"c","text":"AllowUsers noroot"},{"id":"d","text":"RootLogin disabled"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Setting 'PermitRootLogin no' in /etc/ssh/sshd_config is the correct and canonical directive to prevent the root account from authenticating over SSH. 'DenyUsers root' can also block root SSH logins but is not the dedicated directive for this purpose and is considered a secondary control; 'AllowUsers noroot' is not a valid directive, and 'RootLogin disabled' does not exist in sshd_config syntax.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man.openbsd.org/sshd_config#PermitRootLogin","label":"OpenSSH sshd_config man page – PermitRootLogin"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to ensure that no user can log in as root directly via SSH. Which configuration directive in '/etc/ssh/sshd_config' should be set to achieve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security audit reveals that several SUID binaries exist on a production Linux server that should not have the SUID bit set. Which command will find all SUID-enabled files on the entire filesystem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"find / -perm /4000 -type f"},{"id":"b","text":"ls -lR / | grep 'rws'"},{"id":"c","text":"locate --suid /"},{"id":"d","text":"stat / --format='%A' | grep s"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'find / -perm /4000 -type f' searches the entire filesystem for regular files that have the SUID bit (octal 4000) set. The '/4000' notation means 'any file where at least this permission bit is set.' While 'ls -lR' can visually show 's' in permissions, it is not a reliable programmatic search method and is easy to misinterpret. 'locate --suid' is not a valid locate option, and 'stat' with that syntax cannot scan the whole filesystem for SUID bits.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/findutils/manual/html_mono/find.html#Mode-Bits","label":"GNU find manual – Permissions"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security audit reveals that several SUID binaries exist on a production Linux server that should not have the SUID bit set. Which command will find all SUID-enabled files on the entire filesystem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to use mandatory access control (MAC) on a Red Hat Enterprise Linux system to confine processes to only the resources they need. Which security framework is enabled by default on RHEL to provide this capability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"AppArmor"},{"id":"b","text":"SELinux"},{"id":"c","text":"Tomoyo"},{"id":"d","text":"Smack"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$SELinux (Security-Enhanced Linux) is the MAC framework shipped and enabled by default on Red Hat Enterprise Linux and its derivatives. It enforces policy-based access controls beyond traditional DAC. AppArmor is the default MAC framework on Debian/Ubuntu-based systems. Tomoyo and Smack are alternative Linux MAC frameworks but are not the default on RHEL and are rarely used in enterprise deployments.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/using_selinux/getting-started-with-selinux_using-selinux","label":"Red Hat – Getting started with SELinux"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to use mandatory access control (MAC) on a Red Hat Enterprise Linux system to confine processes to only the resources they need. Which security framework is enabled by default on RHEL to provide this capability?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator needs to lock a local user account named 'jsmith' immediately to prevent login while preserving the account and its data. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"usermod -L jsmith"},{"id":"b","text":"passwd --disable jsmith"},{"id":"c","text":"chage -E 0 jsmith"},{"id":"d","text":"userdel -r jsmith"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'usermod -L jsmith' locks the account by prepending a '!' to the hashed password in /etc/shadow, preventing password-based authentication while keeping the account and home directory intact. 'passwd --disable' is not valid syntax for most Linux distributions; the correct passwd flag would be '-l', not '--disable'. 'chage -E 0' expires the account immediately but is a different mechanism (account expiry date) rather than a direct lock. 'userdel -r' would delete the account and its home directory entirely, which does not meet the requirement of preserving the data.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/usermod.8.html","label":"Linux man page – usermod(8)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator needs to lock a local user account named 'jsmith' immediately to prevent login while preserving the account and its data. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator reviews the /etc/sudoers file and finds the following line:

  %developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2

What does this entry allow?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Members of the 'developers' group can restart apache2 as any user on any host without entering a password."},{"id":"b","text":"The user named 'developers' can run any command on all hosts as root without a password."},{"id":"c","text":"Members of the 'developers' group can run all systemctl commands on any host without a password."},{"id":"d","text":"Members of the 'developers' group can restart apache2, but only after entering the root password."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$In sudoers syntax, a '%' prefix denotes a group, so '%developers' refers to all members of the 'developers' group. 'ALL=(ALL)' means from any host, running as any user. 'NOPASSWD:' waives the password requirement. The command is restricted to '/usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2' only. Option b is wrong because 'developers' without '%' would be a user, and the command scope is restricted. Option c is wrong because only the specific 'restart apache2' subcommand is permitted. Option d contradicts the NOPASSWD directive.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/sudoers.5.html","label":"Linux man page – sudoers(5)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator reviews the /etc/sudoers file and finds the following line:

  %developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2

What does this entry allow?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to configure the Linux firewall to drop all incoming traffic on port 23 (Telnet) using firewalld. Which command correctly adds a permanent rule to block this traffic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=23/tcp --zone=block"},{"id":"b","text":"firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=public --remove-service=telnet"},{"id":"c","text":"firewall-cmd --permanent --zone=public --add-rich-rule='rule family=ipv4 port port=23 protocol=tcp drop'"},{"id":"d","text":"firewall-cmd --permanent --direct --add-rule ipv4 filter INPUT 0 -p tcp --dport 23 -j REJECT"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$A rich rule with 'drop' action explicitly drops packets on port 23/tcp for IPv4, which is the most direct way to block Telnet traffic using firewalld's rich-rule syntax. Option a adds port 23 to the 'block' zone, but this only takes effect if the interface is assigned to the block zone, making it unreliable. Option b removes the telnet service definition, but if telnet was never explicitly added as a service, this has no effect and does not add a drop rule. Option d uses the legacy direct interface with REJECT (not DROP) and targets the filter/INPUT chain, which is a valid but deprecated approach and uses REJECT rather than the required DROP action.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_firewalls_and_packet_filters/using-and-configuring-firewalld_firewall-packet-filters#adding-rich-rules_configuring-complex-firewall-rules-with-the-rich-language-syntax","label":"Red Hat – Using and configuring firewalld – Rich rules"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to configure the Linux firewall to drop all incoming traffic on port 23 (Telnet) using firewalld. Which command correctly adds a permanent rule to block this traffic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer needs to audit which files have been modified in the /etc directory within the last 24 hours to check for unauthorized changes. Which command achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"find /etc -mtime -1 -type f"},{"id":"b","text":"find /etc -atime -1 -type f"},{"id":"c","text":"find /etc -ctime +1 -type f"},{"id":"d","text":"stat /etc -newer 24"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'find /etc -mtime -1 -type f' searches for regular files whose modification time (mtime) is less than 1 day ago (i.e., within the last 24 hours). The '-mtime -1' predicate means 'modified less than 1*24 hours ago'. Option b uses '-atime' which tracks access time, not modification time, so it would return files that were read, not changed. Option c uses '-ctime +1' which finds files with a status change time MORE than 24 hours ago — the opposite of what is needed, and ctime tracks inode changes rather than content modification. Option d is not valid syntax; 'stat' does not support a '-newer 24' flag.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/findutils/manual/html_mono/find.html#Age-Ranges","label":"GNU find manual – Time comparisons"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer needs to audit which files have been modified in the /etc directory within the last 24 hours to check for unauthorized changes. Which command achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator is writing a Bash script that iterates over a list of running container names returned by 'docker ps --format "{{.Names}}"' and restarts any container whose name begins with 'web_'. Which script fragment correctly implements this logic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"for container in $(docker ps --format \"{{.Names}}\"); do\n  if [[ $container == web_* ]]; then\n    docker restart \"$container\"\n  fi\ndone"},{"id":"b","text":"for container in $(docker ps --format \"{{.Names}}\"); do\n  if [ $container -eq \"web_*\" ]; then\n    docker restart \"$container\"\n  fi\ndone"},{"id":"c","text":"for container in $(docker ps --format \"{{.Names}}\"); do\n  if grep -q \"^web_\" $container; then\n    docker restart \"$container\"\n  fi\ndone"},{"id":"d","text":"for container in $(docker ps --format \"{{.Names}}\"); do\n  if [[ $container =~ ^web ]]; then\n    docker restart \"$container\"\n  fi\ndone"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because the Bash [[ ]] conditional with the glob pattern 'web_*' accurately matches any string that begins with 'web_' followed by any characters. The double-bracket construct supports glob-style pattern matching on the right-hand side of ==, making this the idiomatic and correct approach. Option B is incorrect because -eq is an arithmetic (integer) comparison operator, not a string or pattern operator, so it will produce an error or unexpected results when used with a string glob. Option C is incorrect because grep reads from a file or stdin — passing a container name directly as a positional argument treats it as a filename, not the text to search, so the logic will not work as intended. Option D is incorrect because the regex '^web' would also match strings like 'webserver' or 'webapp' that do not contain the required underscore, making the filter too broad compared to the intended 'web_' prefix requirement.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Conditional-Constructs","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Conditional Constructs"},{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/ls/","label":"Docker CLI Reference – docker ps"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator is writing a Bash script that iterates over a list of running container names returned by 'docker ps --format "{{.Names}}"' and restarts any container whose name begins with 'web_'. Which script fragment correctly implements this logic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer needs to pass a sensitive database password into a container at runtime without baking the value into the container image or the Dockerfile. The deployment uses a single Docker host (no orchestration platform). Which method best satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Add the password as an ENV instruction in the Dockerfile so it is available inside the container."},{"id":"b","text":"Pass the password at runtime using the docker run -e option (e.g., docker run -e DB_PASS='secret' ...) and source the value from a shell variable or a local .env file that is excluded from version control."},{"id":"c","text":"Write the password into a LABEL instruction in the Dockerfile so it is stored as metadata and not in the environment."},{"id":"d","text":"Hard-code the password directly in the application's configuration file and COPY it into the image during the build."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Option B is correct. Using 'docker run -e' injects the environment variable only at runtime, keeping the sensitive value out of the image layers entirely. Sourcing the value from a shell variable or a .env file (excluded via .gitignore) prevents it from being committed to version control, which aligns with security best practices for single-host Docker deployments. Option A is incorrect because an ENV instruction in the Dockerfile bakes the value into every image layer, making it visible to anyone who can inspect the image with 'docker inspect' or 'docker history'. Option C is incorrect because LABEL also stores the value in the image metadata and is equally visible via 'docker inspect'; it provides no security improvement over ENV in the image. Option D is incorrect because hard-coding credentials in a file that is COPYed into the image is the least secure approach — the secret is permanently embedded in the image filesystem layer and will appear in the build history.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/build/building/best-practices/#exclude-with-dockerignore","label":"Docker Documentation – Keep secrets out of images (Best practices for writing Dockerfiles)"},{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/run/#env","label":"Docker CLI Reference – docker run (-e flag)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer needs to pass a sensitive database password into a container at runtime without baking the value into the container image or the Dockerfile. The deployment uses a single Docker host (no orchestration platform). Which method best satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a server is experiencing high load averages but CPU utilization appears normal. Running `vmstat 1 5` reveals that the 'b' column consistently shows values greater than 10. What is the most likely cause of this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Too many zombie processes are consuming CPU cycles"},{"id":"b","text":"Processes are blocked waiting for I/O, indicating an I/O bottleneck"},{"id":"c","text":"The kernel is running out of virtual memory and swapping excessively"},{"id":"d","text":"Network interface saturation is causing packet drops and retransmissions"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$In `vmstat` output, the 'b' column represents the number of processes in uninterruptible sleep, which means they are blocked waiting for I/O (disk, network, etc.). High values in the 'b' column combined with normal CPU usage strongly indicate an I/O bottleneck — processes are waiting on storage or network I/O rather than consuming CPU. Zombie processes (option a) appear in the 'z' column and do not consume CPU. Swap activity would be reflected in the 'si' and 'so' columns (option c). Network saturation (option d) would be detected with tools like `sar -n DEV` or `netstat`, not directly via the 'b' column.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/vmstat.8.html","label":"vmstat man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a server is experiencing high load averages but CPU utilization appears normal. Running `vmstat 1 5` reveals that the 'b' column consistently shows values greater than 10. What is the most likely cause of this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user reports that after a recent package update, the system boots into emergency mode. The administrator examines `/etc/fstab` and suspects a misconfigured mount entry. Which command should the administrator run FIRST to validate the syntax of `/etc/fstab` without actually mounting any filesystems?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"mount -a"},{"id":"b","text":"fsck -n /etc/fstab"},{"id":"c","text":"findmnt --verify"},{"id":"d","text":"blkid --check /etc/fstab"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`findmnt --verify` reads `/etc/fstab` and checks it for errors, including syntax problems, missing devices, and invalid mount options, without actually performing any mount operations. This makes it the safest first step when diagnosing fstab issues. `mount -a` (option a) attempts to mount all entries and could fail or cause further issues if the fstab is malformed. `fsck` (option b) checks filesystem integrity on block devices, not fstab syntax. `blkid` (option d) lists block device attributes and does not validate fstab at all.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/findmnt.8.html","label":"findmnt man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/1058913","label":"Red Hat – How to diagnose fstab issues"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user reports that after a recent package update, the system boots into emergency mode. The administrator examines `/etc/fstab` and suspects a misconfigured mount entry. Which command should the administrator run FIRST to validate the syntax of `/etc/fstab` without actually mounting any filesystems?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a CentOS Stream 9 server where a critical service named `appd` fails to start. Running `systemctl status appd` shows the unit is in a failed state with exit code 1. Which command will display the most detailed log output specifically for the `appd` service since the last boot?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"tail -f /var/log/syslog | grep appd"},{"id":"b","text":"journalctl -u appd -b"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl log appd --since boot"},{"id":"d","text":"dmesg | grep appd"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`journalctl -u appd -b` queries the systemd journal for all log entries related to the `appd` unit (`-u appd`) from the current boot (`-b`). This provides the most comprehensive and structured view of service-specific log data. `tail -f /var/log/syslog` (option a) may not exist on all systemd-based distros and does not filter per-unit as effectively. `systemctl log` (option c) is not a valid subcommand. `dmesg` (option d) shows kernel ring buffer messages and would not contain userspace service logs.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/journalctl.1.html","label":"journalctl man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/journalctl.html","label":"systemd.journal – Freedesktop documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a CentOS Stream 9 server where a critical service named `appd` fails to start. Running `systemctl status appd` shows the unit is in a failed state with exit code 1. Which command will display the most detailed log output specifically for the `appd` service since the last boot?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server's root filesystem has become read-only after a sudden power loss. The administrator remounts it as read-write and attempts to repair it. Which sequence of commands is correct to safely check and repair the root filesystem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Run `fsck /` while the filesystem is mounted read-write, then reboot"},{"id":"b","text":"Boot into single-user or rescue mode, remount root as read-only, then run `fsck /dev/sda1`"},{"id":"c","text":"Run `e2fsck -f /dev/sda1` while the system is in normal multi-user mode"},{"id":"d","text":"Run `mount --remount,ro /` followed by `fsck /dev/sda1` without rebooting in any special mode"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Running `fsck` on a mounted filesystem risks data corruption. The correct approach is to boot into single-user or rescue mode (where the root filesystem can be mounted read-only or unmounted), then run `fsck /dev/sda1` (or the appropriate device) against the unmounted or read-only partition. Option a is dangerous because the filesystem is still mounted read-write. Option c runs `e2fsck` on a live mounted filesystem, which can cause severe corruption. Option d remounts root read-only in a running system, but critical processes may still be writing, making this unreliable without a proper rescue environment.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/fsck.8.html","label":"fsck man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/e2fsck.8.html","label":"e2fsck man page – Linux manual"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server's root filesystem has become read-only after a sudden power loss. The administrator remounts it as read-write and attempts to repair it. Which sequence of commands is correct to safely check and repair the root filesystem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After adding a new static route on a Linux server, a junior administrator confirms the route appears in the routing table with `ip route show`, but traffic destined for the new subnet is still being dropped. A packet capture on the outbound interface shows packets leaving, but no replies return. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The route was added with an incorrect subnet mask, causing packets to be misrouted locally"},{"id":"b","text":"IPv4 forwarding is disabled on the Linux server"},{"id":"c","text":"The remote network does not have a return route back to the Linux server's network"},{"id":"d","text":"The firewall's INPUT chain is dropping inbound ICMP packets"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$If packets are leaving the server and arriving at the destination network but no replies return, the most likely cause is an asymmetric routing problem — the remote network lacks a return route to the source. The scenario states packets ARE leaving (ruling out local misrouting and forwarding issues). Option a would cause packets to not reach the correct next-hop. Option b (IP forwarding disabled) would prevent the server from forwarding transit traffic, but if the server itself is the source, this is not directly relevant. Option d involves ICMP drops on the INPUT chain, but the problem is the absence of ANY reply, indicating the remote side cannot route back.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ip-route.8.html","label":"ip-route man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://lartc.org/howto/lartc.iproute2.html","label":"Linux Advanced Routing & Traffic Control HOWTO"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After adding a new static route on a Linux server, a junior administrator confirms the route appears in the routing table with `ip route show`, but traffic destined for the new subnet is still being dropped. A packet capture on the outbound interface shows packets leaving, but no replies return. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator runs `df -h` and notices the root filesystem is at 100% utilization, but `du -sh /*` reveals only 60% of space is accounted for. What is the MOST likely explanation for this discrepancy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The filesystem has journal overhead consuming the remaining space"},{"id":"b","text":"Deleted files are still held open by running processes and not yet released"},{"id":"c","text":"The filesystem reserved-blocks percentage is consuming the unaccounted space"},{"id":"d","text":"Hidden directories at the root level are not being scanned by `du`"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When files are deleted on Linux, if a process still holds an open file descriptor to that file, the inode and disk blocks are not released until the process closes the file or is terminated. `du` shows current directory entries (deleted files no longer appear), while `df` reflects actual block usage including blocks held by open-but-deleted files. This is a very common cause of `df` and `du` disagreeing. `lsof | grep deleted` is the typical tool to find such files. Option a (journal overhead) is small and would not account for 40% of a filesystem. Option c (reserved blocks) is typically 5% by default. Option d is possible but unlikely to account for such a large gap.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lsof.8.html","label":"lsof man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://www.linuxfoundation.org/blog/blog/classic-sysadmin-linux-101-5-commands-for-checking-disk-space","label":"Linux Foundation – Understanding df vs du discrepancies"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator runs `df -h` and notices the root filesystem is at 100% utilization, but `du -sh /*` reveals only 60% of space is accounted for. What is the MOST likely explanation for this discrepancy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer complains that a Python application server process is intermittently crashing with an 'out of memory' error, but `free -m` always shows available RAM. An administrator suspects memory overcommitment. Which file should the administrator inspect to understand the kernel's current memory overcommit policy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/proc/sys/vm/swappiness"},{"id":"b","text":"/proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory"},{"id":"c","text":"/proc/meminfo"},{"id":"d","text":"/proc/sys/kernel/panic_on_oom"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`/proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory` controls the kernel's memory overcommitment policy. A value of 0 (default) allows heuristic overcommit, 1 always allows overcommit, and 2 disables overcommit (strict accounting). When set to 2 and the system's commit limit is reached, new memory allocations fail even if physical RAM appears free, which matches the described symptom. `/proc/sys/vm/swappiness` (option a) controls the tendency to swap, not overcommit policy. `/proc/meminfo` (option c) shows memory statistics but not the overcommit policy. `/proc/sys/kernel/panic_on_oom` (option d) controls OOM killer behavior, not the policy itself.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/vm/overcommit-accounting","label":"Linux kernel documentation – vm/overcommit-accounting"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/proc.5.html","label":"proc(5) man page – Linux manual"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer complains that a Python application server process is intermittently crashing with an 'out of memory' error, but `free -m` always shows available RAM. An administrator suspects memory overcommitment. Which file should the administrator inspect to understand the kernel's current memory overcommit policy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems administrator is troubleshooting a server that randomly loses network connectivity every few hours. The interface comes back up on its own after a few minutes. Running `ip link show eth0` during an outage shows the interface state as UP, but `ethtool eth0` shows 'Link detected: no'. What does this indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The Network Manager service has crashed and needs to be restarted"},{"id":"b","text":"There is a physical layer (Layer 1) problem, such as a faulty cable or port on the switch"},{"id":"c","text":"The interface's MTU is misconfigured, causing packet fragmentation and dropped connections"},{"id":"d","text":"The IP address has been released by the DHCP server and not renewed in time"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`ethtool eth0` reporting 'Link detected: no' while the logical interface state is UP indicates that the physical link signal (Layer 1) is absent. The OS sees the interface as administratively up but the NIC cannot detect an electrical or optical signal from the connected switch port. This is a strong indicator of a physical problem: a damaged cable, a loose connector, a failing NIC, or an intermittent switch port. NetworkManager crashes (option a) would not cause 'Link detected: no'. MTU misconfiguration (option c) does not affect physical link detection. DHCP lease expiry (option d) would cause an IP loss but would not affect the physical link status reported by ethtool.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ethtool.8.html","label":"ethtool man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_and_managing_networking/monitoring-and-troubleshooting-network-connections_configuring-and-managing-networking","label":"Red Hat – Using ethtool to troubleshoot network interfaces"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems administrator is troubleshooting a server that randomly loses network connectivity every few hours. The interface comes back up on its own after a few minutes. Running `ip link show eth0` during an outage shows the interface state as UP, but `ethtool eth0` shows 'Link detected: no'. What does this indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator receives an alert that a production server's system time has drifted significantly. The server uses `chronyd` for NTP synchronization. Which command should the administrator use to check the current synchronization sources and their offset values?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ntpq -p"},{"id":"b","text":"timedatectl list-timezones"},{"id":"c","text":"chronyc sources -v"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl status chronyd --full"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`chronyc sources -v` connects to the running `chronyd` daemon and displays all configured NTP sources along with their current state, reachability, polling interval, and offset values. The `-v` flag provides verbose column headers, making it easier to interpret the output. This is the correct tool when `chronyd` is in use. `ntpq -p` (option a) is the query tool for `ntpd`, not `chronyd`, and will fail if ntpd is not running. `timedatectl list-timezones` (option b) lists available timezone names, which is irrelevant to NTP offset diagnosis. `systemctl status chronyd` (option d) shows the service status but does not display peer offset data.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chronyc.1.html","label":"chronyc man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/configuring_basic_system_settings/using-chrony-to-configure-ntp_configuring-basic-system-settings","label":"Red Hat – Configuring NTP using the chrony suite"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator receives an alert that a production server's system time has drifted significantly. The server uses `chronyd` for NTP synchronization. Which command should the administrator use to check the current synchronization sources and their offset values?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator needs to identify which process has a specific TCP port 8443 open on a Linux server, but the `netstat` package is not installed. Which alternative command will display the process name and PID associated with TCP port 8443?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"lsof -i TCP:8443"},{"id":"b","text":"ps aux | grep 8443"},{"id":"c","text":"strace -e network -p 1"},{"id":"d","text":"cat /proc/net/tcp | grep 8443"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`lsof -i TCP:8443` lists all open files matching the TCP protocol on port 8443, and includes the process name, PID, user, and file descriptor. This is a direct replacement for `netstat -tlnp` on systems where `net-tools` is not installed. `ps aux | grep 8443` (option b) would only find processes whose command line contains the string '8443', which is unreliable — many processes listen on a port without including it in their argv. `strace` (option c) traces system calls of a specific PID and is not a port-lookup tool. `cat /proc/net/tcp` (option d) shows raw hex values for ports and inodes but requires manual conversion and cross-referencing with `/proc/[pid]/fd` to identify the process — it does not directly show process names.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lsof.8.html","label":"lsof man page – Linux manual"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ss.8.html","label":"ss man page – Linux manual (modern netstat replacement)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P4$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator needs to identify which process has a specific TCP port 8443 open on a Linux server, but the `netstat` package is not installed. Which alternative command will display the process name and PID associated with TCP port 8443?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator is troubleshooting a system that randomly freezes under heavy load. After reviewing '/var/log/messages', they find repeated kernel messages containing 'Out of memory: Kill process'. Which file, when tuned appropriately, would MOST directly help prevent the OOM killer from terminating critical processes?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/proc/sys/vm/swappiness"},{"id":"b","text":"/proc/[PID]/oom_score_adj"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/security/limits.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"/proc/sys/kernel/panic"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'/proc/[PID]/oom_score_adj' allows per-process tuning of the OOM (Out-of-Memory) killer's selection preference. Writing a value of -1000 to this file for a specific PID effectively disables OOM killing for that process, while positive values make it more likely to be killed. This is the most direct method to protect critical processes. '/proc/sys/vm/swappiness' controls how aggressively the kernel uses swap, which may help overall memory pressure but doesn't protect specific processes. '/etc/security/limits.conf' sets resource limits (like max memory) for users/sessions but doesn't influence OOM killer priority. '/proc/sys/kernel/panic' configures the kernel behavior after a panic, unrelated to OOM handling.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/latest/admin-guide/mm/concepts.html#oom-killer","label":"Linux kernel documentation: OOM killer"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/monitoring_and_managing_system_status_and_performance/configuring-an-out-of-memory-killer_monitoring-and-managing-system-status-and-performance","label":"Red Hat - Configuring the Out-of-Memory Killer"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator is troubleshooting a system that randomly freezes under heavy load. After reviewing '/var/log/messages', they find repeated kernel messages containing 'Out of memory: Kill process'. Which file, when tuned appropriately, would MOST directly help prevent the OOM killer from terminating critical processes?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer reports that a cron job configured in their crontab is not executing at the scheduled time. The cron daemon is running. The crontab entry is: '30 8 * * 1-5 /home/dev/scripts/report.sh'. The administrator verifies the script exists and is executable. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason the job is not running?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The cron daemon requires a SIGHUP signal to reload user crontabs after editing"},{"id":"b","text":"The script relies on environment variables set in ~/.bashrc that are not available in the cron environment"},{"id":"c","text":"Cron jobs cannot be run as non-root users on modern Linux systems"},{"id":"d","text":"The '1-5' weekday range is invalid syntax and must be written as 'Mon-Fri'"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Cron executes jobs with a minimal, non-interactive shell environment that does not source user profile files like '~/.bashrc' or '~/.bash_profile'. If the script depends on environment variables (such as PATH, custom app paths, or credentials) defined in those files, the job will silently fail or behave unexpectedly. The fix is to define required environment variables at the top of the crontab or use full paths within the script. The cron daemon does NOT need a SIGHUP signal to pick up user crontab changes — 'crontab -e' handles this automatically. Non-root users can absolutely run cron jobs. The '1-5' weekday range is valid crontab syntax representing Monday through Friday.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"Linux man page: crontab(5)"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/automating_system_tasks/assembly_scheduling-tasks-with-cron_automating-system-tasks","label":"Red Hat - Automating system tasks with cron"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer reports that a cron job configured in their crontab is not executing at the scheduled time. The cron daemon is running. The crontab entry is: '30 8 * * 1-5 /home/dev/scripts/report.sh'. The administrator verifies the script exists and is executable. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason the job is not running?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default runlevel so that the system boots into multi-user mode without a graphical interface on a systemd-based distribution. Which command should the administrator use to accomplish this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl set-default multi-user.target"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl isolate graphical.target"},{"id":"c","text":"chkconfig --level 3 on"},{"id":"d","text":"update-rc.d multi-user defaults"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$On systemd-based Linux distributions, 'systemctl set-default multi-user.target' sets the default boot target to multi-user (equivalent to runlevel 3), which provides a full multi-user environment without a graphical interface. This command creates a symlink from /etc/systemd/system/default.target to multi-user.target and persists across reboots. Option (b) 'systemctl isolate' switches to a target immediately but does not persist across reboots. Options (c) and (d) are legacy SysVinit/Upstart commands that do not apply to systemd-based systems and would not achieve the desired result.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd.special.html","label":"systemd.special – systemd special units and targets"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to change the default runlevel so that the system boots into multi-user mode without a graphical interface on a systemd-based distribution. Which command should the administrator use to accomplish this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to schedule a one-time task to run a backup script located at /usr/local/bin/backup.sh at 11:30 PM tonight on a Linux system. Which command syntax correctly accomplishes this using the appropriate scheduling utility?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"crontab -e and add: 30 23 * * * /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"b","text":"at 23:30 and then type: /usr/local/bin/backup.sh at the prompt"},{"id":"c","text":"batch 23:30 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl schedule --time=23:30 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'at' command is the correct tool for scheduling a one-time (non-recurring) task in Linux. Running 'at 23:30' opens an interactive prompt where the administrator types the command to execute, then presses Ctrl+D to submit. Option (a) uses crontab, which is designed for recurring scheduled tasks, not one-time execution; the entry shown would run the script every day at 23:30, not just tonight. Option (c) is incorrect because 'batch' does not accept a time argument — it runs jobs when system load allows, without a specific time. Option (d) is invalid; 'systemctl schedule' is not a real systemctl sub-command.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/at.1p.html","label":"at(1) – Linux man page"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to schedule a one-time task to run a backup script located at /usr/local/bin/backup.sh at 11:30 PM tonight on a Linux system. Which command syntax correctly accomplishes this using the appropriate scheduling utility?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems administrator notices that a newly attached 1 TB disk (/dev/sdb) is not yet partitioned or formatted. The administrator creates a single partition using fdisk, then needs to format it with the XFS filesystem and mount it persistently at /data. After formatting the partition /dev/sdb1 with XFS, which file must be edited to ensure the mount persists across reboots?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/mtab"},{"id":"b","text":"/proc/mounts"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/fstab"},{"id":"d","text":"/etc/exports"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$/etc/fstab (filesystem table) is the configuration file that defines how disk partitions, filesystems, and other block devices should be mounted at boot time. Adding an entry such as '/dev/sdb1 /data xfs defaults 0 0' (or preferably using the UUID) ensures the filesystem is automatically mounted on each reboot. Option (a) /etc/mtab is a dynamic file maintained by the kernel/mount that lists currently mounted filesystems; editing it manually is not the correct approach and changes are not persistent. Option (b) /proc/mounts is a read-only kernel interface reflecting current mounts and cannot be edited. Option (d) /etc/exports is used to configure NFS shared directories, which is unrelated to local disk mounting.$patch$, $patch$System Management$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/fstab.5.html","label":"fstab(5) – Linux man page"},{"url":"https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_file_systems/assembly_mounting-file-systems_managing-file-systems","label":"Red Hat – Mounting file systems persistently using /etc/fstab"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems administrator notices that a newly attached 1 TB disk (/dev/sdb) is not yet partitioned or formatted. The administrator creates a single partition using fdisk, then needs to format it with the XFS filesystem and mount it persistently at /data. After formatting the partition /dev/sdb1 with XFS, which file must be edited to ensure the mount persists across reboots?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to ensure that no user can set the SUID bit on any newly created executable files in the /data partition. Which mount option should be added to the /data entry in /etc/fstab to enforce this restriction?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"noexec"},{"id":"b","text":"nosuid"},{"id":"c","text":"nodev"},{"id":"d","text":"ro"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'nosuid' mount option prevents the SUID and SGID bits from taking effect on executables within the mounted filesystem, which mitigates privilege escalation attacks. 'noexec' prevents execution of any binary on the partition entirely but does not specifically target the SUID bit. 'nodev' disallows interpretation of block or character special devices. 'ro' mounts the filesystem read-only, which would prevent file creation altogether but does not specifically address the SUID bit on existing files.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/mount.8.html","label":"Linux man page: mount(8) — Mount Options"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to ensure that no user can set the SUID bit on any newly created executable files in the /data partition. Which mount option should be added to the /data entry in /etc/fstab to enforce this restriction?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is reviewing the sudoers file and finds the following entry:

  %developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2

Which statement BEST describes the security implication of this configuration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Members of the developers group can restart apache2 as any user without providing a password, which could allow service disruption without accountability."},{"id":"b","text":"Members of the developers group can execute any command as root without a password, creating a significant privilege escalation risk."},{"id":"c","text":"Only the root user can restart apache2 using this sudo rule; the developers group is explicitly denied."},{"id":"d","text":"The NOPASSWD directive requires a PAM module to be configured separately before it takes effect."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The entry '%developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2' grants all members of the 'developers' group the ability to run only the 'systemctl restart apache2' command as any user (due to (ALL)) without a password. This is a targeted but accountable risk — they are limited to that one command, but the lack of password prompting reduces auditability. Option B is incorrect because the rule is restricted to a single command, not ALL commands. Option C is incorrect; the % prefix means it applies to the group, not denies it. Option D is incorrect; NOPASSWD is a native sudoers directive and does not require separate PAM configuration.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/sudoers.5.html","label":"Linux man page: sudoers(5)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is reviewing the sudoers file and finds the following entry:

  %developers ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2

Which statement BEST describes the security implication of this configuration?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer wants to use firewalld to permanently block all incoming traffic on TCP port 4444 in the 'public' zone. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-port=4444/tcp --permanent"},{"id":"b","text":"firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-port=4444/tcp --permanent && firewall-cmd --reload"},{"id":"c","text":"firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-rich-rule='rule family=ipv4 port port=4444 protocol=tcp drop' --permanent && firewall-cmd --reload"},{"id":"d","text":"firewall-cmd --panic-on"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Adding a rich rule with the 'drop' action explicitly blocks (drops without response) all incoming TCP port 4444 traffic in the public zone permanently. The '--permanent' flag writes the rule to the persistent configuration and '--reload' applies it to the running firewall. Option A would actually OPEN port 4444, not block it. Option B removes a previously opened port but does not add an explicit drop rule — if the zone's default policy is 'drop' this might work indirectly, but the rich rule approach is explicit and correct. Option D enables panic mode which drops all traffic on all interfaces, far beyond the requirement.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/securing_networks/using-and-configuring-firewalld_securing-networks","label":"Red Hat — Using and Configuring firewalld"},{"url":"https://firewalld.org/documentation/man-pages/firewalld.richlanguage.html","label":"firewalld.org — Rich Language Documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer wants to use firewalld to permanently block all incoming traffic on TCP port 4444 in the 'public' zone. Which command accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a suspected compromise, an administrator runs the following command:

  find / -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null

What is the administrator looking for?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Files that are readable by all users on the system"},{"id":"b","text":"Files with the SUID bit set, which run with the file owner's privileges"},{"id":"c","text":"Files with the sticky bit set that prevent deletion by non-owners"},{"id":"d","text":"Files that have been modified in the last 4000 minutes"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The '-perm -4000' option in the find command matches files where the SUID (Set User ID) bit is set, represented by octal 4000. When an SUID binary is executed, it runs with the privileges of the file owner (often root), not the executing user. Attackers commonly plant or exploit SUID binaries for privilege escalation, making this an important post-compromise check. Option A is incorrect — world-readable files would be found with '-perm -o=r'. Option C is incorrect — the sticky bit is octal 1000, not 4000. Option D is incorrect — the '-mmin' flag is used for time-based searches, not '-perm'.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/find.1.html","label":"Linux man page: find(1)"},{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-123/final","label":"NIST — Guide to General Server Security (SP 800-123)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a suspected compromise, an administrator runs the following command:

  find / -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null

What is the administrator looking for?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A junior administrator needs to generate a 4096-bit RSA key pair for SSH authentication and save the private key to /home/jdoe/.ssh/id_rsa without a passphrase. Which command achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -f /home/jdoe/.ssh/id_rsa -N \"\""},{"id":"b","text":"openssl genrsa -out /home/jdoe/.ssh/id_rsa 4096"},{"id":"c","text":"ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -b 4096 -f /home/jdoe/.ssh/id_rsa -N \"\""},{"id":"d","text":"gpg --gen-key --rsa 4096 --output /home/jdoe/.ssh/id_rsa"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The correct command uses 'ssh-keygen' with '-t rsa' to specify RSA, '-b 4096' for the key size, '-f' to set the output file path, and '-N ""' to set an empty passphrase. Option B uses OpenSSL, which generates a raw RSA key in PEM format suitable for TLS, not directly for SSH public key authentication (it does not produce the .pub counterpart in SSH format). Option C is incorrect because ed25519 does not support specifying a key size with '-b'; the 4096 flag would be ignored and the key type would not be RSA. Option D uses GPG, which is for OpenPGP encryption and signing, not SSH key pair generation.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/ssh-keygen.1.html","label":"Linux man page: ssh-keygen(1)"},{"url":"https://www.openssh.com/manual.html","label":"OpenSSH Project Documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A junior administrator needs to generate a 4096-bit RSA key pair for SSH authentication and save the private key to /home/jdoe/.ssh/id_rsa without a passphrase. Which command achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux system administrator needs to configure PAM to lock a user account for 10 minutes after 5 consecutive failed login attempts on a RHEL-based system. Which PAM module should be used and in which configuration file?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"pam_tally2 configured in /etc/pam.d/system-auth"},{"id":"b","text":"pam_faillock configured in /etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth"},{"id":"c","text":"pam_limits configured in /etc/security/limits.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"pam_unix configured in /etc/pam.d/login"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$On modern RHEL-based systems (RHEL 8+/CentOS Stream), 'pam_faillock' is the current recommended module for account lockout after failed authentication attempts; it replaces the deprecated 'pam_tally2'. It must be referenced in both '/etc/pam.d/system-auth' and '/etc/pam.d/password-auth' to cover all authentication paths. The 'deny=5' and 'unlock_time=600' parameters enforce the 5-attempt threshold and 10-minute lockout respectively. Option A is outdated — pam_tally2 was deprecated in RHEL 8 and removed in RHEL 9. Option C is incorrect — pam_limits enforces resource limits (open files, max processes), not login attempt lockout. Option D is incorrect — pam_unix handles traditional password authentication but does not provide lockout functionality.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/security_hardening/configuring-account-lockout_security-hardening","label":"Red Hat — Configuring account lockout with pam_faillock"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/pam_faillock.8.html","label":"Linux man page: pam_faillock(8)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux system administrator needs to configure PAM to lock a user account for 10 minutes after 5 consecutive failed login attempts on a RHEL-based system. Which PAM module should be used and in which configuration file?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to use SELinux to investigate why a web server process is being denied access to a file, even though the traditional DAC (file permission) bits allow it. Which command displays the most recent SELinux denial messages from the audit log?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"sestatus -v"},{"id":"b","text":"ausearch -m avc -ts recent"},{"id":"c","text":"semanage boolean --list"},{"id":"d","text":"restorecon -Rv /var/www/html"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'ausearch -m avc -ts recent' command queries the Linux Audit framework for AVC (Access Vector Cache) denial messages, which are the SELinux denial events written to /var/log/audit/audit.log. The '-ts recent' flag limits results to the last 10 minutes. This is the primary tool for diagnosing SELinux access denials. Option A — 'sestatus -v' shows the current SELinux mode and policy name but does not display denial messages. Option C — 'semanage boolean --list' lists SELinux booleans and their current state, useful for configuration but not for reviewing denials. Option D — 'restorecon -Rv' restores default SELinux file contexts recursively, which is a remediation step, not a diagnostic command.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/using_selinux/troubleshooting-problems-related-to-selinux_using-selinux","label":"Red Hat — Troubleshooting problems related to SELinux"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ausearch.8.html","label":"Linux man page: ausearch(8)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to use SELinux to investigate why a web server process is being denied access to a file, even though the traditional DAC (file permission) bits allow it. Which command displays the most recent SELinux denial messages from the audit log?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security policy requires that all interactive user shells on a Linux server log every command executed to a tamper-evident central syslog server. Which combination of tools BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure HISTFILE for every user in /etc/profile and set HISTSIZE=10000"},{"id":"b","text":"Enable auditd with a rule targeting execve syscalls and forward events to a remote syslog server using rsyslog or auditd's audisp-remote plugin"},{"id":"c","text":"Set the umask to 0022 in /etc/bashrc to ensure command history files are world-readable"},{"id":"d","text":"Install and enable acct (process accounting) and review the lastcomm output locally on each server"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Using 'auditd' with a rule such as '-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -k cmd_exec' captures every command executed via the execve syscall at the kernel level, making it extremely difficult for users to bypass. Forwarding these events to a remote syslog server via the 'audisp-remote' plugin or rsyslog ensures tamper-evidence since a local user cannot easily alter remote logs. Option A relies solely on shell history (HISTFILE/HISTSIZE), which can be trivially bypassed by users who unset HISTFILE or use non-bash shells, and history is stored locally. Option C sets default file creation permissions and has nothing to do with command logging. Option D — process accounting (acct) records basic process metadata but does not capture command arguments and its logs are local, failing the tamper-evident remote requirement.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/security_hardening/auditing-the-system_security-hardening","label":"Red Hat — System Auditing — auditd and audit rules"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/auditd.8.html","label":"Linux man page: auditd(8)"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/audisp-remote.8.html","label":"Linux man page: audisp-remote(8)"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security policy requires that all interactive user shells on a Linux server log every command executed to a tamper-evident central syslog server. Which combination of tools BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to write a Bash script that exits immediately if any command in the script returns a non-zero exit status. Which command should be placed at the top of the script to enforce this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"set -u"},{"id":"b","text":"set -e"},{"id":"c","text":"set -x"},{"id":"d","text":"set -o pipefail"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'set -e' (also written as 'set -o errexit') causes the shell to exit immediately when a command exits with a non-zero status. 'set -u' causes the shell to treat unset variables as errors. 'set -x' enables debug tracing by printing each command before execution. 'set -o pipefail' makes pipelines return the exit status of the last command that failed, but does not cause the script to exit automatically on failure — it is often combined with 'set -e' for comprehensive error handling.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#The-Set-Builtin","label":"GNU Bash Manual – The Set Builtin"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to write a Bash script that exits immediately if any command in the script returns a non-zero exit status. Which command should be placed at the top of the script to enforce this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer wants to run a containerized web application using Docker and ensure the container automatically restarts if it crashes, but does NOT restart if it is manually stopped. Which Docker run flag achieves this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"--restart always"},{"id":"b","text":"--restart on-failure"},{"id":"c","text":"--restart unless-stopped"},{"id":"d","text":"--restart no"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'--restart unless-stopped' restarts the container automatically after a crash or daemon restart, but does NOT restart it if the container was manually stopped by the user. '--restart always' restarts the container in all cases, including after a manual stop and daemon restart, which does not meet the requirement. '--restart on-failure' only restarts on a non-zero exit code and does not persist across Docker daemon restarts by default. '--restart no' disables automatic restarts entirely.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/engine/containers/start-containers-automatically/","label":"Docker Documentation – Start containers automatically"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer wants to run a containerized web application using Docker and ensure the container automatically restarts if it crashes, but does NOT restart if it is manually stopped. Which Docker run flag achieves this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is writing a Bash script and needs to capture the output of the command 'hostname -f' and store it in a variable called FQDN. Which of the following syntax examples correctly accomplishes this using command substitution?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"FQDN=${hostname -f}"},{"id":"b","text":"FQDN=`hostname -f`"},{"id":"c","text":"FQDN=$(hostname -f)"},{"id":"d","text":"FQDN=<<(hostname -f)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The modern and preferred Bash syntax for command substitution is $(...), so 'FQDN=$(hostname -f)' correctly captures the output of the command into the variable. The legacy backtick syntax (`hostname -f`) also technically works but is deprecated in favor of $() because backticks are harder to nest and read. '${hostname -f}' is invalid syntax — the ${} construct is used for parameter expansion, not command execution. '<<(hostname -f)' is not valid Bash command substitution syntax.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Command-Substitution","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Command Substitution"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is writing a Bash script and needs to capture the output of the command 'hostname -f' and store it in a variable called FQDN. Which of the following syntax examples correctly accomplishes this using command substitution?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems engineer needs to define a multi-container application stack consisting of a web server, an application server, and a database using Docker Compose. After creating the 'docker-compose.yml' file, which command should they run to start all services defined in the file in detached mode?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"docker compose start -d"},{"id":"b","text":"docker compose run --detach"},{"id":"c","text":"docker compose up -d"},{"id":"d","text":"docker compose launch --background"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'docker compose up -d' builds (if necessary), creates, starts, and attaches to containers defined in the Compose file, with '-d' (detached mode) running all containers in the background. 'docker compose start' is used to start already-existing stopped containers, not to create and build new ones, and it does not accept a '-d' flag in the same context. 'docker compose run' is used to run a one-off command on a specific service, not to start the entire stack. 'docker compose launch' is not a valid Docker Compose subcommand.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/compose/up/","label":"Docker Documentation – docker compose up"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems engineer needs to define a multi-container application stack consisting of a web server, an application server, and a database using Docker Compose. After creating the 'docker-compose.yml' file, which command should they run to start all services defined in the file in detached mode?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A junior administrator wrote the following cron job entry and asks why it is not executing at the expected time:

  30 8 * * 1-5 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh

The administrator expected the script to run at 8:30 AM every weekday. Which statement correctly describes what this cron entry actually does?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"It runs at 8:30 PM every weekday because the hour field uses 24-hour time starting from 12."},{"id":"b","text":"It runs at 8:30 AM every weekday, which is exactly as the administrator intended."},{"id":"c","text":"It runs every 30 minutes past the hour, 8 hours a day, Monday through Friday."},{"id":"d","text":"It runs at 8:30 AM only on the first through fifth day of each month, not on weekdays."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The cron expression '30 8 * * 1-5' is correctly formatted and does exactly what the administrator intended: it runs at minute 30 of hour 8 (8:30 AM), every day of the month (*), every month (*), on days of the week 1 through 5 (Monday through Friday in standard cron notation). The hour field uses 24-hour time (0–23), so 8 represents 8 AM. The day-of-week field uses 1=Monday through 7=Sunday (or 0=Sunday in some implementations). The entry is valid and behaves as expected, making this a confirmation question testing accurate cron syntax interpretation rather than identifying an error.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"Linux man page – crontab(5)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A junior administrator wrote the following cron job entry and asks why it is not executing at the expected time:

  30 8 * * 1-5 /usr/local/bin/backup.sh

The administrator expected the script to run at 8:30 AM every weekday. Which statement correctly describes what this cron entry actually does?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations engineer wants to build a custom Docker image from a Dockerfile located in the current directory and tag it as 'myapp:v1.0'. Which command correctly builds and tags the image in a single step?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"docker image create -t myapp:v1.0 ."},{"id":"b","text":"docker build --name myapp:v1.0 ."},{"id":"c","text":"docker build -t myapp:v1.0 ."},{"id":"d","text":"docker create -t myapp:v1.0 -f Dockerfile"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'docker build -t myapp:v1.0 .' uses the 'docker build' command with the '-t' (tag) flag to assign the name and tag 'myapp:v1.0' to the resulting image, using the current directory (.) as the build context where Docker looks for the Dockerfile. 'docker image create' is not a valid Docker CLI command. 'docker build --name' is not a valid flag for docker build; the correct flag for naming/tagging is '-t' or '--tag'. 'docker create' creates a new container from an existing image — it does not build an image from a Dockerfile.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/buildx/build/","label":"Docker Documentation – docker build"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations engineer wants to build a custom Docker image from a Dockerfile located in the current directory and tag it as 'myapp:v1.0'. Which command correctly builds and tags the image in a single step?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a web server process is consuming 98% CPU continuously. After running 'top', the PID is identified as 3847. Which command would allow the administrator to immediately reduce the CPU priority of this process without terminating it?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"kill -9 3847"},{"id":"b","text":"renice +15 -p 3847"},{"id":"c","text":"nice -n 15 3847"},{"id":"d","text":"ionice -c 3 -p 3847"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'renice' command is used to alter the scheduling priority of an already-running process. Using 'renice +15 -p 3847' increases the niceness value (lowering the process priority), which reduces its CPU scheduling preference without terminating it. 'kill -9' would terminate the process immediately. 'nice' is used to launch a new process with a specified priority, not adjust an existing one. 'ionice' adjusts I/O scheduling class, not CPU priority.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-linux-xk0-005-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/renice.1.html","label":"Linux man page: renice"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a web server process is consuming 98% CPU continuously. After running 'top', the PID is identified as 3847. Which command would allow the administrator to immediately reduce the CPU priority of this process without terminating it?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator receives reports that users cannot log in via SSH. The SSH daemon appears to be running, but connections are refused. Upon investigation, the administrator runs 'ss -tlnp' and sees no process listening on port 22. Which configuration file should be checked first to determine why sshd is not binding to the expected port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/hosts.allow"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/ssh/sshd_config"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/pam.d/sshd"},{"id":"d","text":"/etc/security/limits.conf"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The primary configuration file for the OpenSSH daemon is '/etc/ssh/sshd_config'. This file controls the port sshd listens on (via the 'Port' directive), the bind address, and many other daemon behaviors. If sshd is not listening on port 22, a misconfigured 'Port' or 'ListenAddress' directive in this file is the most likely cause. '/etc/hosts.allow' is used for TCP wrappers access control, not port binding. '/etc/pam.d/sshd' handles PAM authentication modules. '/etc/security/limits.conf' manages resource limits for users.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/sshd_config.5.html","label":"OpenSSH sshd_config man page"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-linux-xk0-005-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator receives reports that users cannot log in via SSH. The SSH daemon appears to be running, but connections are refused. Upon investigation, the administrator runs 'ss -tlnp' and sees no process listening on port 22. Which configuration file should be checked first to determine why sshd is not binding to the expected port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator finds that a newly created ext4 filesystem is mounted but users cannot write any new files, even though the filesystem appears to have available space. Running 'df -h' shows 40% usage. Which command would BEST help determine if the real constraint is inode exhaustion?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"df -i"},{"id":"b","text":"du -sh /*"},{"id":"c","text":"lsblk -f"},{"id":"d","text":"fsck -n /dev/sdb1"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'df -i' displays inode usage statistics for mounted filesystems, showing the total number of inodes, used inodes, free inodes, and percentage used. When a filesystem runs out of inodes, no new files can be created even if block space is available — this is a common troubleshooting scenario. 'du -sh /*' shows disk usage by directory, which helps with block space but not inodes. 'lsblk -f' shows filesystem types and UUIDs, not inode usage. 'fsck -n' checks the filesystem for errors in read-only mode but is not the most direct tool for checking inode exhaustion.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/df.1.html","label":"Linux man page: df"},{"url":"https://www.redhat.com/sysadmin/inodes-linux-filesystem","label":"Red Hat - What are inodes?"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator finds that a newly created ext4 filesystem is mounted but users cannot write any new files, even though the filesystem appears to have available space. Running 'df -h' shows 40% usage. Which command would BEST help determine if the real constraint is inode exhaustion?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systemd service named 'appserver.service' fails immediately after starting. The administrator runs 'systemctl start appserver.service' and it returns an error. Which command provides the MOST detailed information about why the service failed, including recent log entries?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"systemctl status appserver.service"},{"id":"b","text":"journalctl -u appserver.service -n 50 --no-pager"},{"id":"c","text":"cat /var/log/syslog | grep appserver"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl show appserver.service"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'journalctl -u appserver.service -n 50 --no-pager' queries the systemd journal specifically for the 'appserver' unit, displaying the last 50 log lines without pagination — providing the most complete and detailed log output for diagnosing failures. 'systemctl status' gives a brief overview and a few recent log lines, but is limited in depth. 'cat /var/log/syslog | grep appserver' may not capture all journald entries, especially on systems that don't forward to syslog. 'systemctl show' outputs the unit's low-level properties and configuration, not its runtime log.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/journalctl.1.html","label":"Linux man page: journalctl"},{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/journalctl.html","label":"Freedesktop.org - systemd journal"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systemd service named 'appserver.service' fails immediately after starting. The administrator runs 'systemctl start appserver.service' and it returns an error. Which command provides the MOST detailed information about why the service failed, including recent log entries?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a kernel update, a server fails to boot and drops to an emergency shell. The administrator suspects a misconfigured boot parameter. Which file is the correct location to permanently modify kernel boot parameters on a GRUB2-based system running RHEL/CentOS?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/default/grub"},{"id":"c","text":"/boot/grub2/grubenv"},{"id":"d","text":"/etc/grub.d/10_linux"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$On GRUB2-based systems such as RHEL/CentOS, the correct file for permanently setting kernel boot parameters is '/etc/default/grub'. The 'GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX' variable in this file defines kernel parameters passed at boot. After editing this file, 'grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg' must be run to regenerate the actual GRUB configuration. '/boot/grub2/grub.cfg' is auto-generated and should not be edited directly. '/boot/grub2/grubenv' stores environment variables like the default boot entry. '/etc/grub.d/10_linux' is a script used during grub.cfg generation, not a direct configuration file for end-user edits.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/managing_monitoring_and_updating_the_kernel/configuring-kernel-command-line-parameters_managing-monitoring-and-updating-the-kernel","label":"Red Hat - Working with GRUB 2"},{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/grub/manual/grub/grub.html","label":"GNU GRUB Manual"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a kernel update, a server fails to boot and drops to an emergency shell. The administrator suspects a misconfigured boot parameter. Which file is the correct location to permanently modify kernel boot parameters on a GRUB2-based system running RHEL/CentOS?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server is experiencing intermittent network packet loss to a remote host at 192.168.10.50. The administrator wants to identify at which network hop the packet loss begins. Which command is MOST appropriate for this task?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ping -c 100 192.168.10.50"},{"id":"b","text":"nmap -sn 192.168.10.50"},{"id":"c","text":"mtr 192.168.10.50"},{"id":"d","text":"netstat -rn"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'mtr' (Matt's Traceroute) combines the functionality of 'ping' and 'traceroute' into a single real-time diagnostic tool. It continuously sends packets to each hop along the route and displays latency and packet loss statistics per hop, making it ideal for identifying exactly where in the network path packet loss begins. 'ping' only tests end-to-end reachability, not per-hop statistics. 'nmap -sn' performs host discovery (ping scan) but does not show routing hops. 'netstat -rn' displays the local routing table and does not test remote connectivity.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://github.com/traviscross/mtr","label":"mtr project on GitHub"},{"url":"https://linux.die.net/man/8/mtr","label":"Linux man page: mtr"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server is experiencing intermittent network packet loss to a remote host at 192.168.10.50. The administrator wants to identify at which network hop the packet loss begins. Which command is MOST appropriate for this task?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user reports that a Bash script named 'backup.sh' they created is not executing and returns 'Permission denied'. The file permissions shown by 'ls -l backup.sh' are '-rw-r--r--'. Which command will resolve this issue with the LEAST permissive change?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"chmod 777 backup.sh"},{"id":"b","text":"chmod 755 backup.sh"},{"id":"c","text":"chmod u+x backup.sh"},{"id":"d","text":"chown root backup.sh"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'chmod u+x backup.sh' adds the execute bit only for the file owner (the user), which is the minimum change required to allow the script owner to execute it. This principle of least privilege is preferred over broader permissions. 'chmod 777' grants read, write, and execute to all users — excessively permissive and a security risk. 'chmod 755' grants execute to owner, group, and others — broader than necessary if only the owner needs execution rights. 'chown root' changes the file owner to root, which does not add execute permission and may make the situation worse for the original user.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chmod.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chmod"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-linux-xk0-005-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user reports that a Bash script named 'backup.sh' they created is not executing and returns 'Permission denied'. The file permissions shown by 'ls -l backup.sh' are '-rw-r--r--'. Which command will resolve this issue with the LEAST permissive change?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux system with LVM is reporting that the logical volume '/dev/vg0/lv_data' is running out of space. The volume group 'vg0' still has 20 GB of free extents available. Which sequence of commands correctly extends the logical volume AND resizes the ext4 filesystem online without unmounting?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"lvextend -L +10G /dev/vg0/lv_data && resize2fs /dev/vg0/lv_data"},{"id":"b","text":"vgextend vg0 /dev/sdc && lvextend -L +10G /dev/vg0/lv_data"},{"id":"c","text":"lvresize -L +10G /dev/vg0/lv_data && xfs_growfs /dev/vg0/lv_data"},{"id":"d","text":"lvextend -l +100%FREE /dev/vg0/lv_data && mkfs.ext4 /dev/vg0/lv_data"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$'lvextend -L +10G /dev/vg0/lv_data' increases the size of the logical volume by 10 GB using free extents already in the volume group. 'resize2fs /dev/vg0/lv_data' then expands the ext4 filesystem to fill the newly allocated space — and can be done online (while mounted) on ext4. 'vgextend' is used to add a new physical volume to a volume group, which is unnecessary here since free space already exists. Option C uses 'xfs_growfs' which is the correct tool for XFS, not ext4. Option D uses 'mkfs.ext4' which would destroy all data on the volume by creating a new filesystem.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/configuring_and_managing_logical_volumes/modifying-the-size-of-a-logical-volume_configuring-and-managing-logical-volumes","label":"Red Hat - Modifying the size of a logical volume"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lvextend.8.html","label":"Linux man page: lvextend"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux system with LVM is reporting that the logical volume '/dev/vg0/lv_data' is running out of space. The volume group 'vg0' still has 20 GB of free extents available. Which sequence of commands correctly extends the logical volume AND resizes the ext4 filesystem online without unmounting?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator notices that '/var' is filling up rapidly. After investigating, they find that the systemd journal is consuming excessive disk space. Which command will permanently cap the on-disk size of the systemd journal to 500 MB?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"journalctl --vacuum-size=500M"},{"id":"b","text":"Edit /etc/systemd/journald.conf and set SystemMaxUse=500M, then restart systemd-journald"},{"id":"c","text":"Edit /etc/logrotate.conf and add 'size 500M' for the journal"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl set-property systemd-journald.service MemoryMax=500M"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The persistent disk usage limit for the systemd journal is configured via the 'SystemMaxUse' directive in '/etc/systemd/journald.conf'. Setting 'SystemMaxUse=500M' and restarting the 'systemd-journald' service applies the cap permanently across reboots. 'journalctl --vacuum-size=500M' is a one-time cleanup operation that removes old journal files until the total drops below 500 MB, but it does not prevent future growth beyond that limit. 'logrotate' manages traditional log files in '/var/log' but does not control the binary systemd journal. 'systemctl set-property MemoryMax' limits RAM usage of the journald process, not on-disk journal storage.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/journald.conf.html","label":"Freedesktop.org - journald.conf man page"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/journalctl.1.html","label":"Linux man page: journalctl"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator notices that '/var' is filling up rapidly. After investigating, they find that the systemd journal is consuming excessive disk space. Which command will permanently cap the on-disk size of the systemd journal to 500 MB?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux system boots but the root filesystem is mounted read-only, preventing normal operation. The administrator suspects filesystem corruption. After booting into recovery mode, which command should be run FIRST before attempting to remount the filesystem read-write?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"mount -o remount,rw /"},{"id":"b","text":"fsck -y /dev/sda1"},{"id":"c","text":"e2fsck -p /dev/sda1"},{"id":"d","text":"tune2fs -e remount-ro /dev/sda1"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Before remounting a potentially corrupted filesystem read-write, a filesystem check must be performed first. 'fsck -y /dev/sda1' runs the appropriate filesystem checker for the partition type and automatically answers 'yes' to all repair prompts, correcting errors. This must be done while the filesystem is unmounted (or mounted read-only as in recovery mode). Running 'mount -o remount,rw /' without first repairing corruption could exacerbate data loss. 'e2fsck -p' is also valid for ext filesystems but uses 'preen' mode, which is less aggressive — 'fsck -y' is more thorough. 'tune2fs -e remount-ro' sets the error behavior but does not check or repair the filesystem.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/fsck.8.html","label":"Linux man page: fsck"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/managing_file_systems/checking-and-repairing-a-file-system_managing-file-systems","label":"Red Hat - Checking and repairing a filesystem"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P5$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux system boots but the root filesystem is mounted read-only, preventing normal operation. The administrator suspects filesystem corruption. After booting into recovery mode, which command should be run FIRST before attempting to remount the filesystem read-write?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user reports that after changing their own password using the `passwd` command, they are immediately prompted for a new password again at their next login attempt. Which `chage` output field would MOST directly explain this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Maximum number of days between password change"},{"id":"b","text":"Password expires"},{"id":"c","text":"Minimum number of days between password change set to a value equal to or greater than Maximum number of days"},{"id":"d","text":"Number of days of warning before password expires"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When the minimum password age (set by `chage -m` or `passwd -n`) is set to a value equal to or greater than the maximum password age, the user is forced to change their password immediately at login because the current password is considered expired the moment it is set. This creates a loop where the password must be changed again at every login. 'Password expires' shows a future expiry date. The warning period just controls when warnings are shown. The maximum days field alone does not cause this behavior.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chage.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chage"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/passwd.1.html","label":"Linux man page: passwd"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user reports that after changing their own password using the `passwd` command, they are immediately prompted for a new password again at their next login attempt. Which `chage` output field would MOST directly explain this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator receives alerts that a server's load average has been above 20 for the past 10 minutes, yet the server only has 4 CPU cores and CPU utilization appears moderate. Which command would BEST help identify whether disk I/O is the bottleneck causing the elevated load average?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"mpstat -P ALL 1"},{"id":"b","text":"iostat -xz 1"},{"id":"c","text":"free -m"},{"id":"d","text":"sar -u 1 5"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`iostat -xz 1` provides extended disk I/O statistics including device utilization (`%util`), average wait times (`await`), and throughput. High `%util` or `await` values indicate I/O saturation, which causes processes to enter uninterruptible sleep (D state) and contributes to an elevated load average even when CPU usage is low. `mpstat -P ALL` shows per-CPU utilization but not I/O. `free -m` shows memory usage. `sar -u` reports CPU statistics, which are already known to be moderate.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/iostat.1.html","label":"Linux man page: iostat"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/48603","label":"Red Hat - Understanding load averages"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator receives alerts that a server's load average has been above 20 for the past 10 minutes, yet the server only has 4 CPU cores and CPU utilization appears moderate. Which command would BEST help identify whether disk I/O is the bottleneck causing the elevated load average?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator runs `df -i` and notices that a filesystem shows 100% inode usage but still has substantial free block space. Which of the following symptoms would a user MOST likely experience as a result?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Existing files cannot be read because the inode table is corrupt."},{"id":"b","text":"New files cannot be created even though disk block space is available."},{"id":"c","text":"The filesystem automatically switches to read-only mode to prevent data loss."},{"id":"d","text":"Large files cannot be written because they require multiple inodes."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Every file and directory on a Linux filesystem requires an inode to store its metadata (permissions, ownership, timestamps, data block pointers). When all inodes are exhausted, no new files or directories can be created, even if free block space remains. Existing files can still be read normally. The filesystem does not automatically switch to read-only mode due to inode exhaustion. Files of any size use exactly one inode regardless of their size; only the block pointers within the inode change.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/df.1.html","label":"Linux man page: df"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/managing_file_systems/assembly_overview-of-available-file-systems_managing-file-systems","label":"Red Hat - What are inodes in Linux?"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator runs `df -i` and notices that a filesystem shows 100% inode usage but still has substantial free block space. Which of the following symptoms would a user MOST likely experience as a result?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer reports that a Bash script works when run manually but fails when executed by a cron job with a 'command not found' error. The script calls a binary located at `/usr/local/bin/`. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The cron daemon does not have permission to read the script file."},{"id":"b","text":"Cron runs jobs with a minimal PATH that does not include /usr/local/bin/."},{"id":"c","text":"The script has Windows-style line endings (CRLF) that confuse the shell."},{"id":"d","text":"The cron job entry is missing the MAILTO variable."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Cron executes jobs with a very minimal default `PATH`, typically limited to `/usr/bin` and `/bin`. Because `/usr/local/bin/` is not in this default PATH, binaries located there are not found. The fix is to either use the full absolute path to the binary in the script, or define `PATH` explicitly at the top of the crontab file or the script itself. CRLF line endings would cause a different error (e.g., bad interpreter). The MAILTO variable controls where output is sent, not execution success.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"Linux man page: crontab(5)"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer reports that a Bash script works when run manually but fails when executed by a cron job with a 'command not found' error. The script calls a binary located at `/usr/local/bin/`. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting intermittent packet loss to a remote host. They want to combine the path tracing capability of `traceroute` with the continuous monitoring of `ping`. Which tool is BEST suited for this task?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"nmap -sP <target>"},{"id":"b","text":"mtr <target>"},{"id":"c","text":"netstat -r"},{"id":"d","text":"tcpdump -i eth0 host <target>"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`mtr` (My Traceroute) combines the functionality of `traceroute` and `ping` into a single tool. It continuously sends packets and shows per-hop latency and packet loss statistics in real time, making it ideal for diagnosing intermittent network issues. `nmap -sP` performs host discovery (ping scan). `netstat -r` shows the local routing table. `tcpdump` captures raw packets for inspection but does not provide hop-by-hop path analysis.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.bitwizard.nl/mtr/","label":"mtr project page"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/mtr.8.html","label":"Linux man page: mtr"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting intermittent packet loss to a remote host. They want to combine the path tracing capability of `traceroute` with the continuous monitoring of `ping`. Which tool is BEST suited for this task?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux system running systemd fails to start a custom service. Running `systemctl status myapp.service` shows the state as `failed`. Which command will display the FULL journal output for that specific service to help diagnose the failure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"journalctl -u myapp.service"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl log myapp.service"},{"id":"c","text":"cat /var/log/systemd/myapp.log"},{"id":"d","text":"dmesg | grep myapp"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`journalctl -u myapp.service` queries the systemd journal for all log entries associated with the specified unit (service). This is the standard and most effective way to view full service logs including startup errors. `systemctl log` is not a valid subcommand. Systemd does not write service logs to `/var/log/systemd/` by default. `dmesg` shows kernel ring buffer messages and would only capture kernel-level events, not application stdout/stderr captured by systemd.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/journalctl.1.html","label":"Linux man page: journalctl"},{"url":"https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/journalctl.html","label":"systemd - journalctl documentation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux system running systemd fails to start a custom service. Running `systemctl status myapp.service` shows the state as `failed`. Which command will display the FULL journal output for that specific service to help diagnose the failure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator runs `ip route show` and sees the output below:

`default via 192.168.1.1 dev eth0`
`192.168.1.0/24 dev eth0 proto kernel scope link src 192.168.1.50`

The server cannot reach hosts on the 10.10.0.0/24 subnet. A router at 192.168.1.254 provides connectivity to that subnet. Which command should the administrator run to add a persistent static route?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ip route add 10.10.0.0/24 via 192.168.1.254"},{"id":"b","text":"route add -net 10.10.0.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 gw 192.168.1.254"},{"id":"c","text":"Add `10.10.0.0/24 via 192.168.1.254` to the appropriate network interface configuration file (e.g., /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/route-eth0)"},{"id":"d","text":"Edit /etc/hosts and add an entry for 10.10.0.0"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$For a persistent static route that survives reboots, the route must be added to the appropriate network configuration file. On RHEL/CentOS systems, this is `/etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/route-eth0`. On systems using NetworkManager, `nmcli` can also be used. The `ip route add` and legacy `route add` commands add routes to the kernel routing table temporarily, which are lost on reboot. `/etc/hosts` is for name-to-IP resolution and has no effect on routing.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/configuring_and_managing_networking/configuring-static-routes_configuring-and-managing-networking","label":"Red Hat - Configuring static routes"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ip-route.8.html","label":"Linux man page: ip-route"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator runs `ip route show` and sees the output below:

`default via 192.168.1.1 dev eth0`
`192.168.1.0/24 dev eth0 proto kernel scope link src 192.168.1.50`

The server cannot reach hosts on the 10.10.0.0/24 subnet. A router at 192.168.1.254 provides connectivity to that subnet. Which command should the administrator run to add a persistent static route?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cron job that was working correctly has stopped running. The administrator checks the system and confirms the `crond` daemon is active. Which log file should the administrator examine FIRST to identify why the cron job is not executing?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/var/log/boot.log"},{"id":"b","text":"/var/log/cron"},{"id":"c","text":"/var/log/dmesg"},{"id":"d","text":"/var/log/secure"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`/var/log/cron` (or `/var/log/syslog` on Debian-based systems) records all cron job execution attempts, including failures and permission denials. This is the primary log for diagnosing cron-related issues. `/var/log/boot.log` contains boot-time messages. `/var/log/dmesg` contains kernel ring buffer messages related to hardware and drivers. `/var/log/secure` logs authentication events and is not relevant to cron job scheduling.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/crontab.5.html","label":"Linux man page: crontab"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/configuring_basic_system_settings/assembly_scheduling-tasks_configuring-basic-system-settings","label":"Red Hat - Automating system tasks with cron"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cron job that was working correctly has stopped running. The administrator checks the system and confirms the `crond` daemon is active. Which log file should the administrator examine FIRST to identify why the cron job is not executing?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After upgrading the kernel on a CentOS-based system, the administrator notices the system still boots into the old kernel. Which configuration file controls the default boot entry for the GRUB2 bootloader?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/default/grub"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/grub.d/40_custom"},{"id":"d","text":"/boot/grub2/device.map"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`/etc/default/grub` contains the user-configurable GRUB2 settings including `GRUB_DEFAULT`, which controls which menu entry boots by default. After editing this file, `grub2-mkconfig` must be run to regenerate `/boot/grub2/grub.cfg`. The `grub.cfg` file is auto-generated and should not be edited directly. `/etc/grub.d/40_custom` is used to add custom menu entries, not set the default. `device.map` maps BIOS device names to OS device names.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/managing_monitoring_and_updating_the_kernel/configuring-kernel-command-line-parameters_managing-monitoring-and-updating-the-kernel","label":"Red Hat - Working with GRUB 2"},{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/grub/manual/grub/grub.html","label":"GNU GRUB Manual"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After upgrading the kernel on a CentOS-based system, the administrator notices the system still boots into the old kernel. Which configuration file controls the default boot entry for the GRUB2 bootloader?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux system is experiencing sluggish performance. Running `vmstat 1 5` shows consistently high values in the `si` and `so` columns. What does this indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The system is experiencing high disk I/O wait due to a slow storage device."},{"id":"b","text":"The system is heavily using swap space, indicating memory pressure."},{"id":"c","text":"The system's CPU steal time is elevated, suggesting a hypervisor issue."},{"id":"d","text":"The system has a high number of context switches caused by too many processes."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$In `vmstat` output, `si` (swap in) and `so` (swap out) represent the amount of memory being swapped in from and out to disk per second. Consistently high values in these columns indicate the system is under memory pressure and is actively using swap. High disk I/O wait is shown in the `wa` column under CPU stats. CPU steal time appears in the `st` column. Context switches are reflected in the `cs` column.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/vmstat.8.html","label":"Linux man page: vmstat"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Study Guide"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux system is experiencing sluggish performance. Running `vmstat 1 5` shows consistently high values in the `si` and `so` columns. What does this indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a network connectivity issue and runs `ss -tulnp`. The output shows no service listening on port 8080, but the application configuration file specifies port 8080. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason the service is not listening?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The firewall is blocking inbound connections on port 8080."},{"id":"b","text":"The application process has failed to start or has crashed."},{"id":"c","text":"Port 8080 is already in use by another service."},{"id":"d","text":"The `ss` command requires root privileges to display all listening ports."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$If `ss -tulnp` shows no listener on port 8080, the process is simply not running or failed to bind. A firewall would not hide a listening socket from `ss`, which queries the kernel socket table directly. If port 8080 were in use by another service, `ss` would show that other process listening on it. While `ss` may show limited process info without root, it still displays all listening ports regardless of privilege level.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/ss.8.html","label":"Linux man page: ss"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/sites/default/files/attachments/rh_ip_command_cheatsheet_1214_jcs_print.pdf","label":"Red Hat - Using ss to investigate sockets"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting a network connectivity issue and runs `ss -tulnp`. The output shows no service listening on port 8080, but the application configuration file specifies port 8080. Which of the following is the MOST likely reason the service is not listening?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A user reports they cannot log in via SSH to a remote Linux server. The administrator confirms the SSH daemon is running and the user's password is correct. Reviewing `/var/log/auth.log` reveals the message: `sshd: PAM: User account has expired`. What is the MOST appropriate corrective action?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Run `passwd -u username` to unlock the user account."},{"id":"b","text":"Run `chage -E -1 username` to remove the account expiration date."},{"id":"c","text":"Edit `/etc/pam.d/sshd` and comment out the `account` module line."},{"id":"d","text":"Run `usermod --expiredate 0 username` to disable the account permanently."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$`chage -E -1 username` sets the account expiration date to never (-1), which removes the expiration and allows the user to log in again. `passwd -u` unlocks a password-locked account (different from an expired account). Commenting out the PAM account module is a serious security risk and not appropriate. `usermod --expiredate 0` sets the expiration to January 1, 1970, effectively disabling the account immediately rather than restoring access.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chage.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chage"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/usermod.8.html","label":"Linux man page: usermod"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A user reports they cannot log in via SSH to a remote Linux server. The administrator confirms the SSH daemon is running and the user's password is correct. Reviewing `/var/log/auth.log` reveals the message: `sshd: PAM: User account has expired`. What is the MOST appropriate corrective action?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux server fails to boot and drops into emergency mode. The administrator suspects a bad entry in `/etc/fstab`. Which command should be run FIRST to attempt to remount the root filesystem as read-write so the file can be edited?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"fsck -y /"},{"id":"b","text":"mount -o remount,rw /"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl daemon-reload"},{"id":"d","text":"mount -a"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$In emergency mode, the root filesystem is typically mounted read-only. Before editing `/etc/fstab`, the administrator must remount it as read-write using `mount -o remount,rw /`. Running `fsck` on a mounted filesystem is dangerous and inappropriate here. `systemctl daemon-reload` reloads unit files but does not affect mount state. `mount -a` would attempt to mount all entries in `/etc/fstab`, which could re-trigger the problematic entry and fail again.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/mount.8.html","label":"Linux man page: mount"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/managing_file_systems/assembly_mounting-file-systems_managing-file-systems","label":"Red Hat - How to recover from fstab errors"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux server fails to boot and drops into emergency mode. The administrator suspects a bad entry in `/etc/fstab`. Which command should be run FIRST to attempt to remount the root filesystem as read-write so the file can be edited?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator reports that a partition mounted at `/data` is showing 100% disk usage when running `df -h`, but `du -sh /data/*` reports only 60% of the partition's total space is used. What is the MOST likely cause of this discrepancy?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The filesystem has been corrupted and inode tables are mismatched."},{"id":"b","text":"One or more deleted files still have open file handles holding disk blocks."},{"id":"c","text":"The partition's block size is misaligned with the filesystem."},{"id":"d","text":"The `du` command does not count hidden directories in its total."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When a file is deleted in Linux but a process still has an open file descriptor to it, the disk blocks are not released until the file handle is closed. `df` reports actual block usage at the filesystem level (including these orphaned blocks), while `du` only counts files visible in the directory tree. The fix is to identify the process using `lsof | grep deleted` and either restart it or close the handle. The other options describe real but unrelated issues that would not cause this specific discrepancy pattern.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/lsof.8.html","label":"Linux man page: lsof"},{"url":"https://access.redhat.com/solutions/2316","label":"Red Hat - Why does df and du report different disk usage?"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator reports that a partition mounted at `/data` is showing 100% disk usage when running `df -h`, but `du -sh /data/*` reports only 60% of the partition's total space is used. What is the MOST likely cause of this discrepancy?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a web server process is consuming 98% CPU continuously. After running `top`, the PID is identified as 4821. Which command would allow the administrator to immediately reduce the CPU priority of this process without killing it?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"kill -9 4821"},{"id":"b","text":"renice +15 -p 4821"},{"id":"c","text":"nice -n 15 4821"},{"id":"d","text":"chrt -f 15 -p 4821"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The `renice` command changes the scheduling priority of a running process. Using `renice +15 -p 4821` raises the niceness value (lowering CPU priority) of the already-running process with PID 4821. `nice` is used to start a new process with a given priority, not adjust an existing one. `kill -9` terminates the process outright. `chrt` adjusts real-time scheduling policies, which is a different concept from niceness.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/renice.1.html","label":"Linux man page: renice"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator notices that a web server process is consuming 98% CPU continuously. After running `top`, the PID is identified as 4821. Which command would allow the administrator to immediately reduce the CPU priority of this process without killing it?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer wants to define a multi-container application with two services — a web application and a Redis cache — so they can be started together with a single command using Docker Compose. Which file should they create, and which command starts all defined services in detached mode?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Create 'Dockerfile' and run 'docker compose build -d'"},{"id":"b","text":"Create 'docker-compose.yml' and run 'docker compose up -d'"},{"id":"c","text":"Create 'docker-compose.yml' and run 'docker compose start --detach'"},{"id":"d","text":"Create 'compose.json' and run 'docker compose run -d'"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Docker Compose reads service definitions from a 'docker-compose.yml' (or 'compose.yaml') file and the command 'docker compose up -d' both creates and starts all defined services in detached (background) mode. A Dockerfile defines a single image build process and does not define multi-container orchestration; 'docker compose build' only builds images without starting containers. 'docker compose start' restarts existing stopped containers and does not accept '--detach' as a flag; it does not create containers from scratch. Docker Compose does not use a JSON file format; it requires YAML.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/compose/","label":"Docker Documentation – Docker Compose overview"},{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/compose/up/","label":"Docker Documentation – docker compose up"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer wants to define a multi-container application with two services — a web application and a Redis cache — so they can be started together with a single command using Docker Compose. Which file should they create, and which command starts all defined services in detached mode?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Bash script uses the following conditional: 'if [ -z "$VAR" ]; then'. Under which condition will the body of this 'if' block execute?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"When the variable $VAR contains only numeric characters."},{"id":"b","text":"When the variable $VAR is unset or contains an empty string."},{"id":"c","text":"When the variable $VAR is set and contains a non-empty string."},{"id":"d","text":"When the variable $VAR references a file that does not exist."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The '-z' string test operator in Bash evaluates to true when the length of the given string is zero — meaning the variable is either unset or set to an empty string. It is the logical opposite of '-n', which is true when the string length is non-zero. '-z' does not test for numeric content, file existence (that would be '! -e'), or non-empty values. This test is commonly used for input validation to check whether a required variable has been populated before proceeding.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Bash-Conditional-Expressions","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Bash Conditional Expressions"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Bash script uses the following conditional: 'if [ -z "$VAR" ]; then'. Under which condition will the body of this 'if' block execute?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is reviewing a Dockerfile and notices the instruction 'ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/sbin/nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]'. What is the primary purpose of the ENTRYPOINT instruction in this context?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"It sets environment variables that the Nginx process will inherit at runtime."},{"id":"b","text":"It defines the default executable that runs when the container starts, making the container behave like the Nginx binary."},{"id":"c","text":"It specifies a command that runs only during the image build process, not at container runtime."},{"id":"d","text":"It creates a mount point for external volumes to be attached to the container."}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$ENTRYPOINT configures the container to run a specific executable as its main process when started, effectively making the container behave like that application. Using the exec form (JSON array syntax), as shown here, avoids shell string interpretation and ensures signals are passed directly to the process. The '-g daemon off;' argument keeps Nginx in the foreground, which is required for containers. ENV is used for environment variables, not ENTRYPOINT. RUN executes commands during the image build phase. VOLUME creates mount points for persistent data.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.docker.com/reference/dockerfile/#entrypoint","label":"Docker Documentation – Dockerfile ENTRYPOINT reference"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is reviewing a Dockerfile and notices the instruction 'ENTRYPOINT ["/usr/sbin/nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]'. What is the primary purpose of the ENTRYPOINT instruction in this context?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Bash script needs to iterate over all '.log' files in the '/var/log' directory and print only the filename without its path. Which script snippet correctly accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"for f in /var/log/*.log; do echo $(dirname $f); done"},{"id":"b","text":"for f in /var/log/*.log; do echo $(basename $f); done"},{"id":"c","text":"for f in /var/log/*.log; do echo ${f#*.}; done"},{"id":"d","text":"for f in /var/log/*.log; do echo ${f##/}; done"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'basename' command strips the directory component from a path, returning only the filename. So '$(basename /var/log/syslog.log)' returns 'syslog.log'. 'dirname' returns the directory portion of the path (e.g., '/var/log'), which is the opposite of what is needed. The parameter expansion '${f#*.}' removes the shortest prefix matching '*.', stripping everything up to and including the first dot, which would incorrectly return the file extension only. '${f##/}' removes the leading slash, still leaving the full path structure.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/basename-invocation.html","label":"GNU Coreutils – basename invocation"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Bash script needs to iterate over all '.log' files in the '/var/log' directory and print only the filename without its path. Which script snippet correctly accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A systems engineer is writing an Ansible playbook to ensure the 'httpd' package is installed and at its latest version on all managed hosts. Which Ansible module and state combination should be used in the task?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"ansible.builtin.package with state: present"},{"id":"b","text":"ansible.builtin.yum with state: installed"},{"id":"c","text":"ansible.builtin.package with state: latest"},{"id":"d","text":"ansible.builtin.apt with state: newest"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'ansible.builtin.package' module is a generic package manager module that works across distributions, and 'state: latest' ensures the package is installed and upgraded to the most current version available in the repository. 'state: present' only ensures installation but does not upgrade an already-installed package. The 'ansible.builtin.yum' module with 'state: installed' is distribution-specific and 'installed' is an alias for 'present', not 'latest'. 'ansible.builtin.apt' is Debian/Ubuntu-specific, and 'newest' is not a valid state value in Ansible.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/collections/ansible/builtin/package_module.html","label":"Ansible Documentation – ansible.builtin.package module"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A systems engineer is writing an Ansible playbook to ensure the 'httpd' package is installed and at its latest version on all managed hosts. Which Ansible module and state combination should be used in the task?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator wants to run a containerized Nginx web server in the background, mapping port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container, using Podman. Which command achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"podman run -d -p 8080:80 nginx"},{"id":"b","text":"podman run -it -p 80:8080 nginx"},{"id":"c","text":"podman start -d --port 8080:80 nginx"},{"id":"d","text":"podman run --background --expose 8080:80 nginx"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The command 'podman run -d -p 8080:80 nginx' correctly uses the '-d' flag to run the container in detached (background) mode and '-p hostPort:containerPort' to map host port 8080 to container port 80. Option b reverses the port mapping (80 on host to 8080 in container) and uses '-it' for interactive mode. Option c uses 'podman start', which starts an existing stopped container, not a new one, and '--port' is not a valid flag for it. Option d uses '--background' and '--expose', neither of which are valid Podman flags for this purpose.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://docs.podman.io/en/latest/markdown/podman-run.1.html","label":"Podman Documentation – podman run"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator wants to run a containerized Nginx web server in the background, mapping port 8080 on the host to port 80 in the container, using Podman. Which command achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer needs to pass the output of the 'grep' command as a positional argument to another command rather than piping it through stdin. Which Bash feature accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Process substitution using <(command)"},{"id":"b","text":"Here-document using <<EOF"},{"id":"c","text":"Command grouping using { command; }"},{"id":"d","text":"Subshell execution using (command)"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["a"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$Process substitution (<(command)) allows the output of a command to be treated as a file, making it usable as a positional filename argument to another command. For example, 'diff <(grep pattern file1) <(grep pattern file2)' passes each grep result as a file-like argument. A here-document provides multi-line stdin input. Command grouping runs commands in the current shell without creating a file-like reference. A subshell runs commands in a child shell environment but also does not produce a file-like reference usable as a positional argument.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Process-Substitution","label":"GNU Bash Manual – Process Substitution"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer needs to pass the output of the 'grep' command as a positional argument to another command rather than piping it through stdin. Which Bash feature accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator is writing a Bash script that must exit immediately if any command in the script fails. Which command at the top of the script enforces this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"set -u"},{"id":"b","text":"set -e"},{"id":"c","text":"set -x"},{"id":"d","text":"set -o pipefail"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The 'set -e' option (also known as 'errexit') causes a Bash script to exit immediately when any command returns a non-zero exit status. 'set -u' treats unset variables as errors but does not exit on command failure. 'set -x' enables debug tracing of each command but does not affect exit behavior. 'set -o pipefail' causes a pipeline to return the exit status of the last command that failed, but alone does not exit the script on a simple command failure — it is often combined with 'set -e' for comprehensive error handling.$patch$, $patch$Scripting, Containers, and Automation$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#The-Set-Builtin","label":"GNU Bash Manual – The Set Builtin"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator is writing a Bash script that must exit immediately if any command in the script fails. Which command at the top of the script enforces this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator is hardening an Ubuntu 22.04 server and wants to enforce mandatory access controls (MAC) to confine the nginx web server process so that even if nginx is compromised, the attacker cannot access files outside of predefined paths. Which framework should the administrator configure to achieve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure TCP Wrappers (/etc/hosts.allow and /etc/hosts.deny) with nginx-specific rules"},{"id":"b","text":"Enable and configure an AppArmor profile for the nginx binary"},{"id":"c","text":"Apply restrictive DAC permissions using chmod and chown on the nginx binary"},{"id":"d","text":"Use ulimit to restrict the number of file descriptors the nginx process can open"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$AppArmor is the Mandatory Access Control (MAC) framework included and enabled by default on Ubuntu. It uses per-application profiles to define exactly which files, directories, network sockets, and capabilities a confined process may access. If nginx is compromised, the attacker operates within the AppArmor profile's constraints regardless of Linux DAC permissions or the process's UID. Ubuntu ships with a default nginx AppArmor profile that can be customized and enforced. Option A (TCP Wrappers) controls network-level access to services based on source IP and is not a MAC framework. Option C (chmod/chown) implements Discretionary Access Control (DAC), which can be bypassed by a root-running process. Option D (ulimit) limits resource usage such as file descriptor count but does not restrict which files the process can access.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://ubuntu.com/server/docs/apparmor","label":"Ubuntu Documentation – AppArmor"},{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/apparmor.7.html","label":"Linux man page: apparmor"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator is hardening an Ubuntu 22.04 server and wants to enforce mandatory access controls (MAC) to confine the nginx web server process so that even if nginx is compromised, the attacker cannot access files outside of predefined paths. Which framework should the administrator configure to achieve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer wants to ensure that a critical configuration file /etc/app/config.conf can be read by all users but modified ONLY by root, and that even root cannot accidentally delete or overwrite it without explicitly removing a protection flag first. Which command achieves this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"chmod 444 /etc/app/config.conf"},{"id":"b","text":"chattr +i /etc/app/config.conf"},{"id":"c","text":"chmod 400 /etc/app/config.conf && chown root:root /etc/app/config.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"setfacl -m u:root:r /etc/app/config.conf"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$The chattr +i command sets the immutable attribute on a file using the ext filesystem's extended attributes. Once set, the file cannot be modified, renamed, deleted, or have hard links created to it — even by root — until the attribute is explicitly removed with chattr -i. This directly satisfies the requirement of protecting root from accidental changes. Option A (chmod 444) makes the file read-only for everyone but root can still overwrite it because root bypasses DAC permission checks. Option C (chmod 400) restricts reads to owner only, violating the 'all users can read' requirement. Option D (setfacl) manages access control lists for user/group access but does not prevent root from modifying or deleting the file.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chattr.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chattr"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ Study Guide – File Security"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer wants to ensure that a critical configuration file /etc/app/config.conf can be read by all users but modified ONLY by root, and that even root cannot accidentally delete or overwrite it without explicitly removing a protection flag first. Which command achieves this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is auditing file permissions on a Linux server. They discover the file /usr/bin/passwd has the following permissions: -rwsr-xr-x. What does the 's' in the owner execute position signify, and what security risk does it introduce?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"The sticky bit is set, preventing users other than the owner from deleting the file; risk is minimal"},{"id":"b","text":"The SetGID bit is set, causing the file to execute with the group owner's privileges; risk is unauthorized group-level privilege escalation"},{"id":"c","text":"The SetUID bit is set, causing the file to execute with the file owner's (root) privileges regardless of who runs it; risk is privilege escalation if the binary is exploitable"},{"id":"d","text":"The file is immutable and cannot be modified; risk is that legitimate updates are blocked"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["c"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$When the SetUID (SUID) bit is set on an executable, the process runs with the effective user ID of the file's owner rather than the user who invoked it. Because /usr/bin/passwd is owned by root, any user running it temporarily gains root-level privileges to update /etc/shadow. This is intentional for passwd but represents a serious privilege-escalation vector if an SUID binary is vulnerable to exploits. Option A describes the sticky bit (typically set on directories). Option B describes SetGID (shown as 's' in the group execute position, not the owner position). Option D describes the immutable attribute set via chattr, which is unrelated to permission bits.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/chmod.1.html","label":"Linux man page: chmod – SUID/SGID bits"},{"url":"https://www.redhat.com/sysadmin/linux-file-permissions-explained","label":"Red Hat – Understanding Linux File Permissions"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is auditing file permissions on a Linux server. They discover the file /usr/bin/passwd has the following permissions: -rwsr-xr-x. What does the 's' in the owner execute position signify, and what security risk does it introduce?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Linux administrator needs to configure the system so that all failed SSH login attempts are automatically blocked after 5 failures within 60 seconds. Which tool or combination provides the MOST appropriate solution natively on most modern Linux distributions?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType", $patch$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure /etc/hosts.deny with a threshold rule and restart xinetd"},{"id":"b","text":"Install and configure fail2ban with an sshd jail definition"},{"id":"c","text":"Use iptables with the LIMIT module and manually parse /var/log/auth.log"},{"id":"d","text":"Set MaxAuthTries to 5 in /etc/ssh/sshd_config and restart the sshd service"}]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$["b"]$patch$::jsonb, $patch$fail2ban monitors log files (e.g., /var/log/auth.log or journald) and dynamically updates firewall rules (iptables/nftables) to block IP addresses that exceed a configurable failure threshold within a time window. Its sshd jail is purpose-built for exactly this use case. Option A (hosts.deny/xinetd) is deprecated and has no dynamic threshold mechanism. Option C (iptables LIMIT) rate-limits packets globally, not per-source-IP after N failures, and requires custom scripting. Option D (MaxAuthTries) only limits retries per connection session, not across multiple connection attempts from the same host, and does not block the source IP.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$, 3, $patch$[{"url":"https://www.fail2ban.org/wiki/index.php/MANUAL_0_8","label":"fail2ban Official Documentation"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/linux","label":"CompTIA Linux+ XK0-005 Exam Objectives"}]$patch$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'manual:xk0-005-topup', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $patch$XK0-005-P6$patch$
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Linux administrator needs to configure the system so that all failed SSH login attempts are automatically blocked after 5 failures within 60 seconds. Which tool or combination provides the MOST appropriate solution natively on most modern Linux distributions?$patch$);

